{"title_page": "1705 in Wales", "text_new": "{{Use Welsh English|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Year in Wales header|1705}}\nThis article is about the particular significance of the year '''1705''' to [[Wales]] and [[Welsh people|its people]].\n\n==Incumbents==\n*[[Prince of Wales]] - ''vacant''\n*[[Princess of Wales]] - ''vacant''\n\n==Events==\n*[[29 April]] - [[George Bull]] is consecrated [[Bishop of St David's]].<ref>{{cite book|author=John Lempri\u00e8re|title=Universal Biography: Containing a Copious Account, Critical and Historical, of the Life and Character, Labors and Actions of Eminent Persons|url=https://archive.org/details/universalbiogra00lempgoog|year=1810|publisher=E. Sargeant|pages=247}}</ref>\n*May\u2013June - In the [[1705 English general election]], [[Richard Bulkeley, 4th Viscount Bulkeley]], becomes MP for Anglesey, and [[Sir Thomas Powell, 1st Baronet]], is MP for Monmouth Boroughs.<ref>{{cite book|author=Great Britain. Parliament. House of Commons|title=Parliamentary Papers|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=L1ETAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA8|year=1878|publisher=H.M. Stationery Office|pages=8}}</ref>\n*''date unknown'' - [[Edward Brereton]] is replaced as MP for Denbigh after having offended the local gentry.<ref>{{cite book|author1=David Hayton|author2=Eveline Cruickshanks|author3=Stuart Handley|title=The House of Commons, 1690-1715|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XdphWLO1xLsC&pg=PA140|year=2002|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-78318-7|pages=140}}</ref>\n\n==Arts and literature==\n===New books===\n*[[Myles Davies]] - ''The Recantation of Mr. Pollett, a Roman priest''\n*[[Thomas Edwards (orientalist)|Thomas Edwardes]] - ''Diocesan Episcopacy proved from Holy Scripture''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://biography.wales/article/s-EDWA-THO-1652|title=Edwardes, Thomas (1652-1721), cleric and Coptic scholar|author=Dafydd Rhys ap Thomas|website=Dictionary of Welsh Biography|publisher=National Library of Wales|access-date=20 June 2019}}</ref>\n*''Letters of Orinda to Poliarchus'' (the letters of [[Katherine Philips]] (posthumously published)\n*Walter Morgan - ''The Parson's Jewel''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://biography.wales/article/s-MORG-WAL-1695|title=Morgan, Walter (fl. 1695), author|author=Walter Thomas Morgan|website=Dictionary of Welsh Biography|publisher=National Library of Wales|access-date=2 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Births==\n*[[6 May]] - [[William Morris (botanist)|William Morris]], botanist, one of the Morris brothers of Anglesey (d. [[1763 in Wales|1763]])\n*''date unknown''\n**[[David Evans (Canon at St Asaph)|David Evans]], Canon of St Asaph  (d. [[1788 in Wales|1788]])<ref>{{cite web|title= Evans, David (1705&ndash;1788), cleric, author, and musician |url=http://wbo.llgc.org.uk/en/s-EVAN-DAV-1705.html|work=Welsh Biography Online|publisher=[[National Library of Wales]]|year=2007|last=Griffith|first=Robert David|accessdate=2 March 2009}}</ref>\n**[[Dafydd Nicolas]], poet (d. [[1774 in Wales|1774]])\n\n==Deaths==\n*''date unknown'' - [[Lionel Wafer]], explorer, 65\n\n==See also==\n*[[1705 in Scotland]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n[[Category:1700s in Wales]]\n[[Category:Years of the 18th century in Wales]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Welsh English|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Year in Wales header|1705}}\nThis article is about the particular significance of the year '''1705''' to [[Wales]] and [[Welsh people|its people]].\n\n==Incumbents==\n*[[Prince of Wales]] - ''vacant''\n*[[Princess of Wales]] - ''vacant''\n\n==Events==\n*[[29 April]] - [[George Bull]] is consecrated [[Bishop of St David's]].<ref>{{cite book|author=John Lempri\u00e8re|title=Universal Biography: Containing a Copious Account, Critical and Historical, of the Life and Character, Labors and Actions of Eminent Persons|url=https://archive.org/details/universalbiogra00lempgoog|year=1810|publisher=E. Sargeant|pages=247}}</ref>\n*May\u2013June - In the [[1705 English general election]], [[Richard Bulkeley, 4th Viscount Bulkeley]], becomes MP for Anglesey, and [[Sir Thomas Powell, 1st Baronet]], is MP for Monmouth Boroughs.<ref>{{cite book|author=Great Britain. Parliament. House of Commons|title=Parliamentary Papers|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=L1ETAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA8|year=1878|publisher=H.M. Stationery Office|pages=8}}</ref>\n*''date unknown'' - [[Edward Brereton]] is replaced as MP for Denbigh after having offended the local gentry.<ref>{{cite book|author1=David Hayton|author2=Eveline Cruickshanks|author3=Stuart Handley|title=The House of Commons, 1690-1715|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XdphWLO1xLsC&pg=PA140|year=2002|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-78318-7|pages=140}}</ref>\n\n==Arts and literature==\n===New books===\n*[[Myles Davies]] - ''The Recantation of Mr. Pollett, a Roman priest''\n*[[Thomas Edwards (orientalist)|Thomas Edwardes]] - ''Diocesan Episcopacy proved from Holy Scripture''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://biography.wales/article/s-EDWA-THO-1652|title=Edwardes, Thomas (1652-1721), cleric and Coptic scholar|author=Dafydd Rhys ap Thomas|website=Dictionary of Welsh Biography|publisher=National Library of Wales|access-date=20 June 2019}}</ref>\n*''Letters of Orinda to Poliarchus'' (the letters of [[Katherine Philips]] (posthumously published)\n*Walter Morgan - ''The Parson's Jewel''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://biography.wales/article/s-MORG-WAL-1695|title=Morgan, Walter (fl. 1695), author|author=Walter Thomas Morgan|website=Dictionary of Welsh Biography|publisher=National Library of Wales|access-date=2 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Births==\n*[[6 May]] - [[William Morris (botanist)|William Morris]], botanist, one of the Morris brothers of Anglesey (d. [[1763 in Wales|1763]])\n*''date unknown''\n**[[David Evans (Canon at St Asaph)|David Evans]], Canon of St Asaph  (d. [[1788 in Wales|1788]])<ref>{{cite web|title= Evans, David (1705&ndash;1788), cleric, author, and musician |url=http://wbo.llgc.org.uk/en/s-EVAN-DAV-1705.html|work=Welsh Biography Online|publisher=[[National Library of Wales]]|year=2007|last=Griffith|first=Robert David|accessdate=2 March 2009}}</ref>\n**[[Dafydd Nicolas]], poet (d. [[1774 in Wales|1774]])\n\n==Deaths==\n*''date unknown'' - [[Lionel Wafer]], explorer, 65\n\n==See also==\n*[[1705 in Scotland]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Years of the 18th century in Wales]]\n", "name_user": "Deb", "label": "safe", "comment": "cat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1705_in_Wales"}
{"title_page": "Cyrus K. Holliday", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name    = Cyrus K. Holliday\n| image      = Cyrus K Holliday.jpg\n| caption   =\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date|1826|4|3|mf=y}}\n| birth_place  = [[Kidderminster, Pennsylvania|Kidderminster]], [[Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n| death_date   = {{death date and age|1900|3|29|1826|4|3|mf=y}}\n| death_place  =Topeka, Kansas, U.S.\n| occupation      = [[rail transport|Railroad]] executive\n| parents         = David Holliday<br>Mary (Kennedy) Holliday\n| spouse          = Mary Dillon Jones\n| children        = Lillie Holliday<br>Charles King Holliday\n}}\nColonel '''Cyrus Kurtz Holliday''' (April 3, 1826 &ndash; March 29, 1900) was an American railroad executive who was one of the founders of the township of [[Topeka, Kansas]], in the mid 19th century;<ref name=\"findagrave\">{{cite web| work=Findagrave.com| url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/6532533| title=Cyrus K. Holliday| accessdate=December 7, 2005}}</ref><ref name=\"History of Kansas\">{{cite book| title=A Standard History of Kansas and Kansans| chapterurl=http://skyways.lib.ks.us/genweb/archives/1918ks/bioh/hollidck.html| chapter=Cyrus K. Holliday| last=Connelly| first=William E.| location=Chicago| publisher=Lewis Publishing Company| orig-year=1918| edition=transcribed| year=1997}}</ref>  and was [[Adjutant General of Kansas]] during the [[American Civil War]]. The title ''Colonel'', however, was honorary. He was the first president of the [[Atchison, Topeka and Santa Fe Railway]], as well as one of the railroad's directors for nearly 40 years, up to 1900. A number of railway locomotives have been named after him, as well as the former town of [[Holliday, Kansas]]. He was also the Deputy Grand Master of the [[Grand Lodge of Kansas|Grand Lodge A.F. & A.M. of Kansas]]. As a Freemason, he was a member of Topeka Lodge #17 and was highly influential in the decision of moving the State Capitol to the city of Topeka. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.masonic.benemerito.net/msricf/papers/marples/marples-unionpacific.freemasonry.nebraska.pdf|title=UNION  PACIFIC, FREEMASONRY,  AND  NEBRASKA|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Education and early career==\nHe was born on April 3, 1826, to David and Mary (Kennedy) Holliday, in [[Kidderminster, Pennsylvania|Kidderminster]], [[Pennsylvania]] (near [[Carlisle, Pennsylvania|Carlisle]]).<ref name=\"History of Kansas\" /><ref name=Waters24>Waters, p. 24.</ref><ref name=\"Territorial Kansas\">{{cite web| work=Territorial Kansas Online| date=September 16, 2003| url=http://www.territorialkansasonline.org/cgiwrap/imlskto/index.php?SCREEN=bio_sketches/holliday_cyrus| title=Cyrus K. Holliday, 1826-1900| accessdate=March 27, 2007}}</ref> The younger Holliday received a public school education, graduating from [[Allegheny College]] in [[Meadville, Pennsylvania]], where he studied law, in 1852. Although he moved to [[Kansas]] in 1854, Allegheny College's alumni records show Holliday receiving a master's degree in 1855.<ref name=Waters24 />\n\nWhile he was still in Meadville, he was asked to prepare legal documentation for a new railroad that would connect to the city. The proposed railroad (likely the [[Pittsburgh and Erie Railroad]] which was sometimes known as \"The Meadville Line\") would almost connect with a larger nearby system (the [[Atlantic and Great Western Railroad]]), which meant that it could become a feeder route to the larger railroad. Holliday saw the potential of the line and instead of asking for a standard fee to create the documents, he asked for and was granted a partnership in the new railroad. When this railroad was purchased by the larger system, Holliday earned [[United States dollar|$]]20,000 from the sale.<ref name=\"History of Kansas\" />\n\nAfter the sale was completed, he married Mary Dillon Jones. He soon followed the many others making the migration to settle land west of the [[Mississippi River]], but Mary stayed behind in Pennsylvania. The two were reunited later in Kansas after the births of their children, Lillie and Charles King.\n\n==Founding Topeka and military service==\nIn 1854 he moved to Kansas, leaving his wife behind in Pennsylvania to follow later.  He first settled in [[Lawrence, Kansas|Lawrence]] in October 1854. On December 10, 1854, after helping to find a location for the new townsite of Topeka, he wrote a letter to his wife saying:\n\n<blockquote>I am now thirty miles above Lawrence on the Kansas River assisting in starting a new town. We are just about in the central portion of the \"settled\" Territory and with perhaps the best landing and the most eligible site for a city in the entire country. ... So I think it must be, and in a few years when civilization by its magic influence shall have transformed this glorious country from what it is now to the brilliant destiny awaiting it, the Sun in all his course will visit no land more truly lovely and desirable than this. Here, Mary, with God's kind permission, we will make our home; and I have every reason to believe a home it will truly be.<ref>{{cite web| publisher=The Capital-Journal| date=March 8, 2003| url=http://cjonline.com/stories/030903/our_hollidaytext.shtml| title=Cyrus K. Holliday -- A letter home| accessdate=July 4, 2005| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040223193936/http://cjonline.com/stories/030903/our_hollidaytext.shtml| archive-date=February 23, 2004| url-status=dead}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nIn 1855 Holliday received the honorary title of Colonel for supervising a regiment during the [[Wakarusa War]].  He also served as the [[Adjutant General of Kansas]] during the [[American Civil War|Civil War]] from May 2, 1864 to March 31, 1865.  Although his Colonel title was only honorary, he continued to use it long after his military service.<ref name=\"Territorial Kansas\" />\n\nIn 1861, Holliday served in the [[Kansas State Senate]], and although he ran for Congress in 1874, he was defeated in that election. He was a Republican.<ref name=\"History of Kansas\" />\n\nHolliday had broad interests in developing the natural resources of Kansas. In the 1890s he became mistakenly convinced that Ellis and Trego counties in central Kansas contained mineral deposits of [[tin]], [[zinc]], and [[gold]]. In 1899 his son [[Charles K. Holliday]] founded [[Smoky Hill City, Kansas]] near the supposed mineral deposits.<ref>{{cite journal| author=Plazak, Dan| year=2007| title=The imaginary gold mines of Kansas| journal=Mining History Journal| volume=14| pages=11\u201322 }}</ref>\n\n==Santa Fe Railroad==\nOnce Topeka was founded, it needed transportation to connect it to the rest of the country.  Holliday's legal skills were called on again to create the paperwork for a new railroad. In 1859 he singlehandedly wrote the charter for the Atchison and Topeka Railroad Company, which would connect the two cities by rail following the route of the [[Santa Fe Trail]].<ref name=Waters26>Waters, p. 26.</ref><ref>{{cite book| title=The story of the Santa Fe| page=[https://archive.org/details/storysantafe00bradgoog/page/n64 56]| author=Bradley, Glenn D.| location=Boston| publisher=The Gorham Press| year=1920| url=https://archive.org/details/storysantafe00bradgoog| accessdate=March 3, 2010}}</ref><ref name=Blackmar>{{cite book| pages=863\u2013864| url=https://books.google.com/?id=o8X5krq3fP8C| accessdate=March 3, 2010| title=Kansas: A Cyclopedia of State History, Embracing Events, Institutions, Industries, Counties, Cities, Towns, Prominent Persons, Etc.| editor=Blackmar, Frank W.| volume=II| location=Chicago| publisher=Standard Publishing Company| year=1912 }}</ref>  Kansas Territory governor [[Samuel Medary]] approved the charter on February 11, 1859.<ref name=Waters487>Waters, p. 487.</ref>  Holliday was named a director and president of the new railroad on September 17, 1860,<ref name=Waters24 /><ref name=SFPresidents>{{cite journal| title=Santa Fe Officials Past and Present| page=63| journal=Santa Fe Employes' Magazine|date=January 1910| volume=IV| issue=2| url=https://books.google.com/?id=vABLAAAAYAAJ| accessdate=March 3, 2010| publisher=Santa Fe Magazine }}</ref> which was renamed in 1863 to the [[Atchison, Topeka and Santa Fe Railroad]].  During his tenure as president, Holliday secured land grants from the federal government that would soon be used by the railroad to populate the western portion of Kansas in order to build a customer base for the railroad. He stepped down from the presidency at the end of 1863,<ref name=SFPresidents /> but remained on the board of directors until July 27, 1865. He rejoined the board on September 24, 1868, this time serving until his death on March 29, 1900.<ref name=Blackmar /><ref name=SFPresidents /><ref name=Waters346>Waters, p. 346.</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n[[File:Officials at Fair Park, Atchison, Topeka, & Santa Fe, 'Cyrus K. Holliday' Locomotive No. 1 with Tender.jpg|thumb|upright|Officials of the Atchison, Topeka, & Santa Fe, on the line's ''Cyrus K. Holliday'' Locomotive No. 1]]\nHolliday is buried in Topeka Cemetery, [[Topeka, Kansas]].<ref name=\"findagrave\" /> He is memorialized for his contributions to [[Kansas]] and the Santa Fe:\n* ''Cyrus K. Holliday'', Locomotive #1, a vintage locomotive was displayed by the A, T & SF into the 1960s. The locomotive is now preserved in the Kansas History Museum as Santa Fe No. 132.\n* He is portrayed in the 1940 movie \"[[Santa Fe Trail (film)|Santa Fe Trail]]\" by [[Henry O'Neill]] as a promoter of commerce and development in the American West of his time.\n* {{libship honor|name=Cyrus K. Holliday|type=his}}<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.usmm.org/libertyships.html| title=Liberty Ships built by the United States Maritime Commission in World War II| accessdate=March 27, 2007| publisher=American Merchant Marine at War}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.kancoll.org/khq/1947/47_2_henderson.htm| title=Ships in World War II Bearing Kansas Names| author=Henderson, Harold J.| date=May 1947| publisher=Kansas State Historical Society| work=KanColl: The Kansas Historical Quarterlies| accessdate=March 27, 2007}}</ref>\n* Locomotive #1 on the [[Disneyland Railroad]] bore the name \"C.K. Holliday\" since the park's opening in 1955.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.disneylandtoday.com/Railroad/e1train.htm| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010423122443/http://www.disneylandtoday.com/Railroad/e1train.htm| url-status=dead| archive-date=April 23, 2001| title=C.K. Holliday - Engine No. 1| work=The Happiest Place on Earth: The Santa Fe and Disneyland Railroad}}</ref>\n* Locomotive #2 of the [[Disneyland Railroad (Paris)|Euro Disneyland Railroad]] was also named \"C.K. Holliday\" in his honor.\n* In 1960, he was inducted into the [[Hall of Great Westerners]] of the [[National Cowboy & Western Heritage Museum]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Hall of Great Westerners |url=https://nationalcowboymuseum.org/hall-of-great-westerners/ |website=National Cowboy & Western Heritage Museum |accessdate=November 22, 2019}}</ref>\n* The Cyrus Hotel, opening in January 2019, has been named in his honor in Topeka, KS.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n* {{cite book| author=Waters, Lawrence Leslie| year=1950| title=Steel Trails to Santa Fe| publisher=University of Kansas Press, Lawrence, Kansas }}\n\n{{S-start}}\n\n{{S-new}}\n{{S-ttl| title=President of the [[Atchison, Topeka and Santa Fe Railway]]| years=1860 &ndash; 1863 }}\n{{S-aft| after=[[Samuel C. Pomeroy]] }}\n\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{good article}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Holliday, Cyrus K.}}\n[[Category:1826 births]]\n[[Category:1900 deaths]]\n[[Category:Atchison, Topeka and Santa Fe Railway presidents]]\n[[Category:American city founders]]\n[[Category:Kansas state senators]]\n[[Category:Mayors of Topeka, Kansas]]\n[[Category:Kansas Republicans]]\n[[Category:19th-century American politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name    = Cyrus K. Holliday\n| image      = Cyrus K Holliday.jpg\n| caption   =\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date|1826|4|3|mf=y}}\n| birth_place  = [[Kidderminster, Pennsylvania|Kidderminster]], [[Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n| death_date   = {{death date and age|1900|3|29|1826|4|3|mf=y}}\n| death_place  =Topeka, Kansas, U.S.\n| occupation      = [[rail transport|Railroad]] executive\n| parents         = David Holliday<br>Mary (Kennedy) Holliday\n| spouse          = Mary Dillon Jones\n| children        = Lillie Holliday<br>Charles King Holliday\n}}\nColonel '''Cyrus Kurtz Holliday''' (April 3, 1826 &ndash; March 29, 1900) was an American railroad executive who was one of the founders of the township of [[Topeka, Kansas]], in the mid 19th century;<ref name=\"findagrave\">{{cite web| work=Findagrave.com| url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/6532533| title=Cyrus K. Holliday| accessdate=December 7, 2005}}</ref><ref name=\"History of Kansas\">{{cite book| title=A Standard History of Kansas and Kansans| chapterurl=http://skyways.lib.ks.us/genweb/archives/1918ks/bioh/hollidck.html| chapter=Cyrus K. Holliday|author1=Connelly, William E.  | location=Chicago| publisher=Lewis Publishing Company| year=1918; transcribed 1997 }}</ref>  and was [[Adjutant General of Kansas]] during the [[American Civil War]]. The title ''Colonel'', however, was honorary. He was the first president of the [[Atchison, Topeka and Santa Fe Railway]], as well as one of the railroad's directors for nearly 40 years, up to 1900. A number of railway locomotives have been named after him, as well as the former town of [[Holliday, Kansas]]. He was also the Deputy Grand Master of the [[Grand Lodge of Kansas|Grand Lodge A.F. & A.M. of Kansas]]. As a Freemason, he was a member of Topeka Lodge #17 and was highly influential in the decision of moving the State Capitol to the city of Topeka. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.masonic.benemerito.net/msricf/papers/marples/marples-unionpacific.freemasonry.nebraska.pdf|title=UNION  PACIFIC, FREEMASONRY,  AND  NEBRASKA|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Education and early career==\nHe was born on April 3, 1826, to David and Mary (Kennedy) Holliday, in [[Kidderminster, Pennsylvania|Kidderminster]], [[Pennsylvania]] (near [[Carlisle, Pennsylvania|Carlisle]]).<ref name=\"History of Kansas\" /><ref name=Waters24>Waters, p. 24.</ref><ref name=\"Territorial Kansas\">{{cite web| work=Territorial Kansas Online| date=September 16, 2003| url=http://www.territorialkansasonline.org/cgiwrap/imlskto/index.php?SCREEN=bio_sketches/holliday_cyrus| title=Cyrus K. Holliday, 1826-1900| accessdate=March 27, 2007}}</ref> The younger Holliday received a public school education, graduating from [[Allegheny College]] in [[Meadville, Pennsylvania]], where he studied law, in 1852. Although he moved to [[Kansas]] in 1854, Allegheny College's alumni records show Holliday receiving a master's degree in 1855.<ref name=Waters24 />\n\nWhile he was still in Meadville, he was asked to prepare legal documentation for a new railroad that would connect to the city. The proposed railroad (likely the [[Pittsburgh and Erie Railroad]] which was sometimes known as \"The Meadville Line\") would almost connect with a larger nearby system (the [[Atlantic and Great Western Railroad]]), which meant that it could become a feeder route to the larger railroad. Holliday saw the potential of the line and instead of asking for a standard fee to create the documents, he asked for and was granted a partnership in the new railroad. When this railroad was purchased by the larger system, Holliday earned [[United States dollar|$]]20,000 from the sale.<ref name=\"History of Kansas\" />\n\nAfter the sale was completed, he married Mary Dillon Jones. He soon followed the many others making the migration to settle land west of the [[Mississippi River]], but Mary stayed behind in Pennsylvania. The two were reunited later in Kansas after the births of their children, Lillie and Charles King.\n\n==Founding Topeka and military service==\nIn 1854 he moved to Kansas, leaving his wife behind in Pennsylvania to follow later.  He first settled in [[Lawrence, Kansas|Lawrence]] in October 1854. On December 10, 1854, after helping to find a location for the new townsite of Topeka, he wrote a letter to his wife saying:\n\n<blockquote>I am now thirty miles above Lawrence on the Kansas River assisting in starting a new town. We are just about in the central portion of the \"settled\" Territory and with perhaps the best landing and the most eligible site for a city in the entire country. ... So I think it must be, and in a few years when civilization by its magic influence shall have transformed this glorious country from what it is now to the brilliant destiny awaiting it, the Sun in all his course will visit no land more truly lovely and desirable than this. Here, Mary, with God's kind permission, we will make our home; and I have every reason to believe a home it will truly be.<ref>{{cite web| publisher=The Capital-Journal| date=March 8, 2003| url=http://cjonline.com/stories/030903/our_hollidaytext.shtml| title=Cyrus K. Holliday -- A letter home| accessdate=July 4, 2005| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040223193936/http://cjonline.com/stories/030903/our_hollidaytext.shtml| archive-date=February 23, 2004| url-status=dead}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nIn 1855 Holliday received the honorary title of Colonel for supervising a regiment during the [[Wakarusa War]].  He also served as the [[Adjutant General of Kansas]] during the [[American Civil War|Civil War]] from May 2, 1864 to March 31, 1865.  Although his Colonel title was only honorary, he continued to use it long after his military service.<ref name=\"Territorial Kansas\" />\n\nIn 1861, Holliday served in the [[Kansas State Senate]], and although he ran for Congress in 1874, he was defeated in that election. He was a Republican.<ref name=\"History of Kansas\" />\n\nHolliday had broad interests in developing the natural resources of Kansas. In the 1890s he became mistakenly convinced that Ellis and Trego counties in central Kansas contained mineral deposits of [[tin]], [[zinc]], and [[gold]]. In 1899 his son [[Charles K. Holliday]] founded [[Smoky Hill City, Kansas]] near the supposed mineral deposits.<ref>{{cite journal| author=Plazak, Dan| year=2007| title=The imaginary gold mines of Kansas| journal=Mining History Journal| volume=14| pages=11\u201322 }}</ref>\n\n==Santa Fe Railroad==\nOnce Topeka was founded, it needed transportation to connect it to the rest of the country.  Holliday's legal skills were called on again to create the paperwork for a new railroad. In 1859 he singlehandedly wrote the charter for the Atchison and Topeka Railroad Company, which would connect the two cities by rail following the route of the [[Santa Fe Trail]].<ref name=Waters26>Waters, p. 26.</ref><ref>{{cite book| title=The story of the Santa Fe| page=[https://archive.org/details/storysantafe00bradgoog/page/n64 56]| author=Bradley, Glenn D.| location=Boston| publisher=The Gorham Press| year=1920| url=https://archive.org/details/storysantafe00bradgoog| accessdate=March 3, 2010}}</ref><ref name=Blackmar>{{cite book| pages=863\u2013864| url=https://books.google.com/?id=o8X5krq3fP8C| accessdate=March 3, 2010| title=Kansas: A Cyclopedia of State History, Embracing Events, Institutions, Industries, Counties, Cities, Towns, Prominent Persons, Etc.| editor=Blackmar, Frank W.| volume=II| location=Chicago| publisher=Standard Publishing Company| year=1912 }}</ref>  Kansas Territory governor [[Samuel Medary]] approved the charter on February 11, 1859.<ref name=Waters487>Waters, p. 487.</ref>  Holliday was named a director and president of the new railroad on September 17, 1860,<ref name=Waters24 /><ref name=SFPresidents>{{cite journal| title=Santa Fe Officials Past and Present| page=63| journal=Santa Fe Employes' Magazine|date=January 1910| volume=IV| issue=2| url=https://books.google.com/?id=vABLAAAAYAAJ| accessdate=March 3, 2010| publisher=Santa Fe Magazine }}</ref> which was renamed in 1863 to the [[Atchison, Topeka and Santa Fe Railroad]].  During his tenure as president, Holliday secured land grants from the federal government that would soon be used by the railroad to populate the western portion of Kansas in order to build a customer base for the railroad. He stepped down from the presidency at the end of 1863,<ref name=SFPresidents /> but remained on the board of directors until July 27, 1865. He rejoined the board on September 24, 1868, this time serving until his death on March 29, 1900.<ref name=Blackmar /><ref name=SFPresidents /><ref name=Waters346>Waters, p. 346.</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n[[File:Officials at Fair Park, Atchison, Topeka, & Santa Fe, 'Cyrus K. Holliday' Locomotive No. 1 with Tender.jpg|thumb|upright|Officials of the Atchison, Topeka, & Santa Fe, on the line's ''Cyrus K. Holliday'' Locomotive No. 1]]\nHolliday is buried in Topeka Cemetery, [[Topeka, Kansas]].<ref name=\"findagrave\" /> He is memorialized for his contributions to [[Kansas]] and the Santa Fe:\n* ''Cyrus K. Holliday'', Locomotive #1, a vintage locomotive was displayed by the A, T & SF into the 1960s. The locomotive is now preserved in the Kansas History Museum as Santa Fe No. 132.\n* He is portrayed in the 1940 movie \"[[Santa Fe Trail (film)|Santa Fe Trail]]\" by [[Henry O'Neill]] as a promoter of commerce and development in the American West of his time.\n* {{libship honor|name=Cyrus K. Holliday|type=his}}<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.usmm.org/libertyships.html| title=Liberty Ships built by the United States Maritime Commission in World War II| accessdate=March 27, 2007| publisher=American Merchant Marine at War}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.kancoll.org/khq/1947/47_2_henderson.htm| title=Ships in World War II Bearing Kansas Names| author=Henderson, Harold J.| date=May 1947| publisher=Kansas State Historical Society| work=KanColl: The Kansas Historical Quarterlies| accessdate=March 27, 2007}}</ref>\n* Locomotive #1 on the [[Disneyland Railroad]] bore the name \"C.K. Holliday\" since the park's opening in 1955.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.disneylandtoday.com/Railroad/e1train.htm| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010423122443/http://www.disneylandtoday.com/Railroad/e1train.htm| url-status=dead| archive-date=April 23, 2001| title=C.K. Holliday - Engine No. 1| work=The Happiest Place on Earth: The Santa Fe and Disneyland Railroad}}</ref>\n* Locomotive #2 of the [[Disneyland Railroad (Paris)|Euro Disneyland Railroad]] was also named \"C.K. Holliday\" in his honor.\n* In 1960, he was inducted into the [[Hall of Great Westerners]] of the [[National Cowboy & Western Heritage Museum]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Hall of Great Westerners |url=https://nationalcowboymuseum.org/hall-of-great-westerners/ |website=National Cowboy & Western Heritage Museum |accessdate=November 22, 2019}}</ref>\n* The Cyrus Hotel, opening in January 2019, has been named in his honor in Topeka, KS.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n* {{cite book| author=Waters, Lawrence Leslie| year=1950| title=Steel Trails to Santa Fe| publisher=University of Kansas Press, Lawrence, Kansas }}\n\n{{S-start}}\n\n{{S-new}}\n{{S-ttl| title=President of the [[Atchison, Topeka and Santa Fe Railway]]| years=1860 &ndash; 1863 }}\n{{S-aft| after=[[Samuel C. Pomeroy]] }}\n\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{good article}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Holliday, Cyrus K.}}\n[[Category:1826 births]]\n[[Category:1900 deaths]]\n[[Category:Atchison, Topeka and Santa Fe Railway presidents]]\n[[Category:American city founders]]\n[[Category:Kansas state senators]]\n[[Category:Mayors of Topeka, Kansas]]\n[[Category:Kansas Republicans]]\n[[Category:19th-century American politicians]]\n", "name_user": "Slambo", "label": "safe", "comment": "adjust citation to fix error message", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cyrus_K._Holliday"}
{"title_page": "Pharrell Williams", "text_new": "{{pp-vandalism|small=yes}}\n{{short description|American musician}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name             = Pharrell Williams\n| image            = \"Hidden Figures\" Screening at NMAAHC (NHQ201612140033) (cropped).jpg\n| caption          = Williams at the red carpet screening of ''[[Hidden Figures]]'', 2016\n| alias            = {{flatlist|\n* Pharrell\n* Skateboard P\n* Sk8board\n* Auto Goon\n* Magnum, the Verb Lord\n* Station Wagon P\n}}\n| birth_name       = Pharrell Lanscilo Williams<ref name=\"GrammyBio\">{{cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/pharrell-williams|title=Artist: Pharrell Williams|work=Recording Acqdemy}}</ref>\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|1973|4|5}}\n| birth_place      = [[Virginia Beach, Virginia]], U.S.\n| occupation = {{flatlist|\n* Singer\n* rapper\n* songwriter\n* record producer\n* record executive\n* entrepreneur\n* fashion designer\n* A&R representative\n* film/television producer\n}}\n| television = ''[[True and the Rainbow Kingdom]]''<br>''[[Brainchild (TV series)|Brainchild]]''\n| years_active       = 1994\u2013present<ref name=\"Sony/ATV\"/>\n| home_town          = \n| organization       = [[I Am Other]]\n| spouse = {{marriage|Helen Lasichanh|2013}}\n| children = 4\n| awards             = [[List of awards and nominations received by Pharrell Williams|Full list]]\n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist <!-- See WP:WikiProject Musicians -->|embed=yes\n| background   = solo_singer\n| instrument   = {{hlist|Vocals|drums|guitar|keyboards}}\n| genre        = {{flatlist|\n* [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n* [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n* [[funk]]\n* [[Pop music|pop]]\n}}\n| label        = {{flatlist|\n* [[I Am Other]]\n* [[Columbia Records|Columbia]]\n* [[Virgin Records|Virgin]]\n* [[Arista Records|Arista]]\n* [[Interscope Records|Interscope]]\n* [[Star Trak Entertainment|Star Trak]]\n}}\n| associated_acts = <!-- Per Template:Infobox_musical_artist#associated_acts this list is for acts that the musician has been a member of, not just a guest artist. Multiple song projects are required to show important collaboration. --> {{flatlist|\n* [[Ariana Grande]]\n* [[Child Rebel Soldier]]\n* [[N.E.R.D.]]\n* [[The Neptunes]]\n* [[Clipse]]\n* [[Daft Punk]]\n* [[Jay-Z]]\n* [[Justin Timberlake]]\n* [[Kelis]]\n* [[Robin Thicke]]\n* [[Ol' Dirty Bastard]]\n* [[Snoop Dogg]]\n* [[T.I.]]\n* [[Teddy Riley]]\n* [[Tyler, the Creator]]\n* [[Usher (musician)|Usher]]\n}}\n| website = {{URL|pharrellwilliams.com}}\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Pharrell Lanscilo Williams'''<ref name=GrammyBio/> ({{IPAc-en|f|\u0259|\u02c8|\u0279|\u025b|l}}; born April 5, 1973) is an American singer, rapper, songwriter, record producer, fashion designer, and entrepreneur. Williams and [[Chad Hugo]] formed the record production duo [[The Neptunes]] in 1994,<ref name=\"Sony/ATV\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sonyatv.com/en/songwriters/637/pharrell-williams|title=Pharrell Williams|publisher=[[Sony/ATV Music Publishing]]|accessdate=2019-12-02}}</ref> producing [[Hip hop music|hip hop]] and [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] music. He is the lead vocalist of the band [[N.E.R.D|N*E*R*D]], which he formed with Hugo and childhood friend [[Shay Haley]]. Williams also owns [[I Am Other]], a multimedia creative collective that serves as an umbrella for all of Pharrell Williams' endeavors, including [[Billionaire Boys Club (clothing retailer)|Billionaire Boys Club]].\n\nWilliams released his first solo single, \"[[Frontin']]\", in 2003 and followed it with his debut solo album, ''[[In My Mind (Pharrell Williams album)|In My Mind]]'', in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/artists/149f91ef-1287-46da-9a8e-87fee02f1471|title=BBC|accessdate=December 11, 2011}}</ref> His second album, ''[[Girl (Pharrell Williams album)|Girl]]'', was released in March 2014<ref name=\"second album\" /><ref name=\"iTunes GIRL US\">{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/g-i-r-l/id823593445 |title=G I R L by Pharrell Williams |publisher=[[iTunes]] |accessdate=February 24, 2014}}</ref> and included the commercially successful single \"[[Happy (Pharrell Williams song)|Happy]]\". As part of the Neptunes, Williams has produced numerous singles for [[The Neptunes production discography|various recording artists]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/news/music/la-et-nerd-01jun01,0,7745056.story|title=LA Times|accessdate=December 11, 2011 | work=Los Angeles Times|first=Chris|last=Lee|date=June 1, 2008}}</ref> Williams featured on [[Daft Punk]]'s \"[[Get Lucky (Daft Punk song)|Get Lucky]]\" which reached the top ten in the music charts of over 32 countries, and has sold more than 9.3 million copies, making it one of the [[List of best-selling singles|best-selling singles of all time]]. The song won [[Grammy Award for Record of the Year|Record of the Year]] and [[Grammy Award for Best Pop Duo/Group Performance|Best Pop Duo/Group Performance]] at the [[56th Annual Grammy Awards|56th Grammy Awards]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/videos/daft-punk-pharrell-williams-nile-rodgers-win-record-year|title=Daft Punk, Pharrell Williams, Nile Rodgers Win Record Of The|date=2014-01-26|website=GRAMMY.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref>\n\nWilliams has received numerous [[List of awards and nominations received by Pharrell Williams|accolades and nominations]]; he has won 13 [[Grammy Award|Grammy Awards]], including three as [[Producer of the Year, Non-Classical]] (one came as a member of The Neptunes). He is also a two-time [[Academy Award]] nominee, receiving a 2014 [[Academy Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]] nomination for \"Happy\" (which was featured in ''[[Despicable Me 2]]'') and a 2017 [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]] nomination as one of the producers of ''[[Hidden Figures]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nPharrell Lanscilo Williams was born on April 5, 1973, in [[Virginia Beach, Virginia]],<ref name=\"Allmusic\">{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p281403|pure_url=yes}}|title=Pharrell Williams \u2013 Overview|last=Kellman|first=Andy|website=[[Allmusic]]|accessdate=March 5, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"The Guardian\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2005/nov/06/popandrock.pharrellwilliams|title=Just Williams|last=Bainbridge|first=Luke|date=November 5, 2005|work=[[The Guardian]]|publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]]|accessdate=December 13, 2008|location=London}}</ref> the oldest of three sons of {{sic|Pharaoh|hide=yes}} Williams, a handyman, and his wife Carolyn, a teacher.<ref>{{cite web|date=October 13, 2003|title=Pharrell Williams|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|publisher=[[Time Inc.|Time]]|url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20148349,00.html|accessdate=November 28, 2008}}</ref> His roots extend for generations in [[Virginia]] and [[North Carolina]], and one of his ancestors journeyed to [[West Africa]] in 1831, prompting other relatives to emigrate from America to [[Liberia]] in 1832.<ref>{{cite web|date=September 2014|title=Why Pharrell Almost Didn't Exist|work=Megan Smolenyak's Blog|url=http://megansmolenyak.com/pharrell/|accessdate=September 8, 2014}}</ref>\n\nWilliams met [[Chad Hugo]] in a seventh-grade summer band camp where Williams played the keyboards and drums and Hugo played [[tenor saxophone]]. They were also both members of a [[marching band]]; Williams played the [[snare drum]] while Hugo was drum major.<ref name=\"Age\">{{cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2004/05/12/1084289744331.html|title=Like the song? These guys wrote it|last=Campbell|first=Melissa|date=May 15, 2004|work=[[The Age]]|publisher=[[Fairfax Media]]|accessdate=May 22, 2007|location=Melbourne}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9D01E7D9143BF93BA35751C0A9629C8B63&sec=&spon=&pagewanted=all|title=Style; The Sound|last=Frere-Jones|first=Sasha|date=February 8, 2004|work=[[The New York Times]]|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|accessdate=March 5, 2009}}</ref> Williams and Hugo attended [[Princess Anne High School]] where he played in the school band; there Pharrell got the name Skateboard P.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2004/feb/08/entertainment/ca-shiver8|title=Virginia is for hip-hop lovers|last=Shiver Jr.|first=Jube|date=February 8, 2004|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|publisher=[[Tribune Company]]|accessdate=March 5, 2009}}</ref> Hugo attended Kempsville High School. In the [[MTV]] show ''[[When I Was 17]]'', Williams stated that he was a nerd and often did things that made him stand out from most of his peers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PPvuIFDYeKM |title=Pharrell Williams \u2013 When I Was 17 (Full) |publisher=[[YouTube]] |date=2013-07-10 |accessdate=2016-07-09}}</ref>  Williams attended [[Northwestern University]] for two years before dropping out.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/pharrell-williams-profile-happiness-is-his-truth-9463049.html?amp |title=Pharrell Williams - profile: Happiness is his truth |newspaper=[[The Independent]] |date=2014-05-30 |accessdate=2018-04-13}}</ref>\n\nIn the early 1990s, Hugo and Williams formed a four-piece \"R&B-type\" group, [[the Neptunes]], with friends [[Shay Haley]] and Mike Etheridge. They later entered a high school talent show where they were discovered by [[Teddy Riley (producer)|Teddy Riley]], whose studio was next to Princess Anne High School.<ref>[http://www.yolk.com/v092/chadhugo1.html]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060508073207/http://www.yolk.com/v092/chadhugo1.html|date=May 8, 2006}}</ref> After graduating from high school, the group signed with Riley.{{citation needed}}\n\n==Career==\n{{BLP sources section|date=May 2018}}\n\n===1992\u201397: Early career===\nThrough working with Riley, Williams went on to write a verse and help produce for [[Wreckx-N-Effect]]'s 1992 hit \"[[Rump Shaker (song)|Rump Shaker]]\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Kimpel|first=Dan|title=How They Made It|publisher=[[Hal Leonard Corporation]]|year=2006|pages=[https://archive.org/details/howtheymadeittru0000kimp/page/124 124]\u2013125|isbn=0-634-07642-6|url=https://archive.org/details/howtheymadeittru0000kimp|url-access=registration|quote=pharrell williams.|accessdate=March 21, 2009}}</ref> That same year, he also performed a small rap solo on [[SWV]]'s second hit, \"Right Here (UK Remix)\". Williams and Hugo met rap duo [[Clipse]] in Virginia Beach in 1993, where they later signed to [[Arista Records]] through Williams' [[Star Trak Entertainment]] imprint in 2002.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/artists/clipse/articles/story/5938804/new_faces_the_clipse|title=New Faces: The Clipse |last=Brackett|first=Nathan|date=September 13, 2002|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|publisher=[[Jann Wenner|Wenner Media]]|accessdate=March 21, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"Yale Daily News\">{{cite web|url=http://www.yaledailynews.com/articles/view/19305 |title=Rap duo 'Clipse' rocks the gangsta hip-hop scene |last=Torbati |first=June |date=December 8, 2006 |work=[[Yale Daily News]] |accessdate=March 21, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070212024815/http://www.yaledailynews.com/articles/view/19305 |archivedate=February 12, 2007 }}</ref> In 1994, Hugo and Williams had established themselves as a production duo under their old name \"The Neptunes\", and assistant-produced \"Tonight's The Night\" from [[Blackstreet]]'s [[Blackstreet (album)|self-titled album]]. Over the next three years they continued to produce occasionally, and some of the results had little resemblance to the Neptunes' sound later. However, some like [[Mase]]'s 1997 song \"Lookin' at Me\" from his album ''[[Harlem World]]'', and the most definite beginning of the distinctive \"Neptunes sound\", came with [[N.O.R.E]]'s \"Superthug\" in 1998, reaching number 36 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], and gaining them widespread attention for the first time.{{citation needed}}\n\n===1998\u20132004: The Neptunes===\n[[File:PHARRELL WILLIAMS by foto di matti.jpg|thumb|left|Pharrell Williams in Berlin, March 2005]]\nIn 2000, they produced the song \"[[I Just Wanna Love U (Give It 2 Me)]]\" (featuring a chorus by Pharrell himself) for [[Jay Z]]'s album ''[[The Dynasty: Roc La Familia]]'', which released as the album's first single.   The song's sound and success sparked the interest of maturing pop artist\n[[Britney Spears]]. {{citation needed|date=May 2018}}\n\nIn 2001, Britney Spears released her third studio album, ''[[Britney (album)|Britney]]'', featuring the lead single \"[[I'm a Slave 4 U]]\", which was produced by The Neptunes.   \nThe song was a defining hit in both of their careers, and it was The Neptunes' first time having helped create an album that debuted number one in the [[Billboard 200]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1449404/20010928/nerd.jhtml|title=Neptunes\u2019 Pharrell Williams Rethinks R&B|work=MTV News|accessdate=February 13, 2015}}</ref> \nThe same year, [[N.E.R.D]], consisting of Williams, Hugo and Haley, released their first album, ''[[In Search Of... (N.E.R.D album)|In Search of...]]'', in Europe, where the first Kelis album was better received.{{citation needed}} The album sounded very much like their previous production work; the group decided that they should make their work as N.E.R.D sound different, and re-recorded the album with the rock band [[Spymob]].{{citation needed|date=May 2018}}\n\nIn 2002 their re-produced album{{which?}} was released worldwide, and the Neptunes reached number one in the U.S. with Nelly's single, \"[[Hot in Herre]]\". In August of the same year, the Neptunes were named \"Producers of the Year\" at both [[The Source (magazine)|the Source Awards]] and the [[Billboard Music Award]]s.{{citation needed}} [[Clipse]] released their commercial debut album ''[[Lord Willin']]'' in August 2002. The album started at number one on the ''Billboard'' [[Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums]] chart and number four on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], fueled by its first two singles, \"[[Grindin']]\" and \"[[When the Last Time]]\", which peaked at number 34 and number 19 respectively on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100.{{citation needed|date=May 2018|reason=entire paragraph}}\n\nThe Neptunes released a self-credited album called ''[[Clones (album)|The Neptunes Present... Clones]]'' in 2003, with songs and remixes from various artists. This topped the U.S. ''Billboard'' 200 Albums Chart. The Neptunes and Williams specifically were also kept in public eye largely due to ties with [[Jay Z]], producing several hit singles for him and two tracks on his ''[[The Black Album (Jay-Z album)|The Black Album]]''. The track \"[[Frontin']]\" was a big hit.{{citation needed}} A survey in August 2003 found the Neptunes produced almost 20 percent of songs played on British radio at the time, and a survey in the US had them at 43 percent.<ref name=Age/> The same year, the Neptunes remixed the [[Daft Punk]] song \"[[Harder, Better, Faster, Stronger]]\" for the duo's poorly received remix album ''[[Daft Club]]''.  The track also had a brief rap section performed by Williams.<ref name=\"Fekadu\">{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/music/news/2010-11-04-pharrell-williams_N.htm|title=USA Today: Rapper-producer Pharrell has new CD, big plans|last=Fekadu|first=Mesfin|date=April 11, 2010|accessdate=December 11, 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[N.E.R.D|N*E*R*D]]'s second [[funk rock]]-oriented album, ''[[Fly or Die]]'', released in March 2004. Williams's rock credentials were further bolstered by his appearance at the [[2004 Grammy Awards]], performing [[the Beatles]]'s \"[[Please Please Me#\"I Saw Her Standing There\"|I Saw Her Standing There]]\" on drums with [[Sting (musician)|Sting]], [[Dave Matthews]], and [[Vince Gill]]. Williams received two Grammy Awards that night, one for [[Grammy Award for Producer of the Year, Non-Classical|Producer of the Year, Non-Classical]], and another for [[Best Pop Vocal Album]] for his work on [[Justin Timberlake]]'s hit album ''[[Justified (album)|Justified]]''. They also gained their first UK number one, again with [[Nelly]], and \"[[Flap Your Wings (song)|Flap Your Wings]]\".{{citation needed|date=May 2018|reason=entire paragraph}}\n\nIn September 2004, Williams was featured on the [[Snoop Dogg]] single \"[[Drop It Like It's Hot]].\" The song would eventually peak at number one on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] two months later, marking Williams's first number one single in the United States. The song was named \"Rap Song of the Decade\" by ''Billboard'' in 2009.<ref>[https://www.billboard.com/song/snoop-dogg-featuring-pharrell/drop-it-like-it-s-hot/6900789#/charts-decade-end/rap-songs?year=2009]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121103145651/http://www.billboard.com/song/snoop-dogg-featuring-pharrell/drop-it-like-it-s-hot/6900789#/charts-decade-end/rap-songs?year=2009|date=November 3, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2004, [[Gwen Stefani]] released her first debut studio album ''[[Love. Angel. Music. Baby.]]'' which featured the song [[Hollaback Girl]], which was also produced by The Neptunes.  \"Hollaback Girl\" entered the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] at number 82 on the issue dated April 2, 2005,<ref>{{cite web |last=Whitmire |first=Margo |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/63581/50-cent-nets-a-fourth-top-10-hit |title=50 Cent Nets A Fourth Top 10 Hit |work=Billboard |date=March 24, 2005 |accessdate=February 3, 2016}}</ref> and within six weeks of its release, it had reached the top of the chart,<ref>{{cite web |last=Whitmire |first=Margo |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/63105/stefani-single-ousts-50-cent-from-no-1 |title=Stefani Single Ousts 50 Cent From No. 1 |work=Billboard |date=April 28, 2005 |accessdate=February 3, 2016}}</ref> becoming Stefani's first US number one.\n\n===2005\u201309: ''In My Mind''===\n[[File:Astronaut Leland Melvin, and Pharrell Williams present montage to Quincy Jones.jpg|right|thumb|230px|Williams and American astronaut [[Leland D. Melvin]] present a montage to record producer [[Quincy Jones]].]]\nOn September 9, 2005, Williams performed the opening single from his first solo album ''[[In My Mind (Pharrell album)|In My Mind]]'', \"[[Can I Have It Like That]]\", featuring [[Gwen Stefani]]. The single did poorly in the US, reaching only number 48. It fared better in the UK, reaching number three. Between then and the July 25, 2006 release of ''In My Mind'', he released \"[[Angel (Pharrell Williams song)|Angel]]\" (in Europe only), and later \"[[Number One (Pharrell Williams song)|Number One]]\" with [[Kanye West]]. Several songs leaked to the internet before the album release, most notably \"[[In My Mind (Pharrell Williams album)|Mamacita]]\" featuring [[Daddy Yankee]], which was subsequently cut from the final version. \"[[In My Mind (Pharrell Williams album)|That Girl]]\" featuring [[Snoop Dogg]] was the final single.{{citation needed|date=May 2018|reason=entire paragraph}}\n\nIn 2006, the Neptunes produced [[Clipse]]'s second album ''[[Hell Hath No Fury (Clipse album)|Hell Hath No Fury]]''. Most critics labeled the album the Neptunes best production in years, and put the duo back in the charts.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Hell-Hath-No-Fury-Clipse/dp/B0000TWMDY |title=Hell Hath No Fury: Clipse: Music: Reviews, Prices & more |publisher=Amazon.com |date= |accessdate=November 5, 2010}}</ref> A year later, Williams collaborated with [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]], on the song \"[[Hey You (Madonna song)|Hey You]]\", which was available for download on the [[MSN]] website. 25 cents for each of the first one million downloads was donated to the [[Alliance for Climate Protection]], in support of [[Live Earth]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://liveearth.msn.com/green/Madonnadownload |title=Retrieved on May 22, 2007 |publisher=Liveearth.msn.com |date=September 15, 2010 |accessdate=November 5, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080821085106/http://liveearth.msn.com/green/madonnadownload/ |archivedate=August 21, 2008 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Later that year, Williams performed songs at the [[Concert for Diana]] on July 1, 2007. On July 7, he performed at the [[Live Earth concert, Rio de Janeiro|Brazilian leg]] of [[Live Earth (2007 concert)|Live Earth]] in Rio de Janeiro.\n\nA remix album of Williams's solo debut, ''In My Mind'', titled ''Out of My Mind'', was recorded with his newly formed band \"The Yessirs\" featuring [[Questlove]] of [[the Roots]], and was produced by Questlove and keyboardist [[James Poyser]]. However, Williams's record label [[Interscope Records]] did not think that the album would sell well and subsequently was shelved.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thehiphopicon.com/pharrell.htm|title=Pharrell Williams goes Out of His Mind|author=TheHipHopIcon.com|date=September 14, 2007|publisher=TheHipHopIcon.com|accessdate=September 16, 2007}}</ref> The album has built up a strong fanbase asking for its release. The tracks started appearing on Questlove's MySpace, and with every 10,000 plays, a new song was made available. As of July 4, 2007, the full CD has leaked onto the internet along with two songs not featured on ''In My Mind'':  a remix of \"Mamacita\" and \"Creamsickle\".{{citation needed|date=May 2018}}\n\nWilliams produced [[Beyonc\u00e9]]'s version of \"[[Diamonds Are a Girl's Best Friend]]\". He then wrote the Neptunes-produced \"Why Should I Be Sad\" on [[Britney Spears]]' fifth studio album, ''[[Blackout (Britney Spears album)|Blackout]]''. He also produced two songs from [[the Hives]]' album, ''[[The Black and White Album]]'', titled \"[[The Black and White Album|Well All Right!]]\" and \"[[The Black and White Album|T.H.E.H.I.V.E.S.]]\".\n\nIn April 2008, [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] released her eleventh album, ''[[Hard Candy (Madonna album)|Hard Candy]]'', which featured vocals from Williams and production from the Neptunes on several tracks. In June, an article in [[NME]] revealed that Williams was very interested in producing [[the Strokes]]' fourth album.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/pharrell-williams/37303|title=NME News Pharrell Williams: 'I want to produce The Strokes' new album' - NME.COM|date=June 13, 2008|work=NME.COM|accessdate=February 13, 2015}}</ref> Later that year, Williams worked on a remix album for [[Maroon 5]]'s ''[[Call and Response: The Remix Album|Call & Response]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Cohen|first=Jonathan|date=October 31, 2008|title=Pharrell, Oakenfold, Of Montreal Remix Maroon 5|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Nielsen Company|Nielsen Business Media]]|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1043620/pharrell-oakenfold-of-montreal-remix-maroon-5|accessdate=November 2, 2008}}</ref>\n\nWilliams continued working with a variety of artists, including [[Shakira]] on the songs '[[Did It Again (Shakira song)|Did It Again]]', '[[She Wolf (Shakira album)|Why Wait]]', '[[She Wolf (Shakira album)|Good Stuff]]' and '[[She Wolf (Shakira album)|Long Time]]' for her sixth studio album, ''[[She Wolf (Shakira album)|She Wolf]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/music/a181454/shakira-pharrell-taught-me-a-lot.html |title=Music \u2013 News \u2013 Shakira: 'Pharrell taught me a lot' |website=Digital Spy |date=October 10, 2009 |accessdate=November 5, 2010}}</ref> In September 2009, Williams was credited as a co-writer and producer of the song \"[[Fresh Out the Oven]]\" for [[Jennifer Lopez]].<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/17842/102934 |title=Pink, Paramore, Death Cab, Katy Perry, Ne-Yo and More: VMAs Interviews You Didn't See on TV  |magazine=Rolling Stone |accessdate=November 5, 2010}}</ref> It was released as a [[buzz single]] from Lopez's seventh studio album ''[[Love? (album)|Love?]]''. The following month, Williams made a guest appearance on French rapper [[Uffie]]'s first album, which arrived in early 2010.<ref name=\"Busy P Blog 10/03/2009\">{{cite web|url=http://busyp.coolcats.fr/2009/10/uffie-pop-the-lock-video/ |title=Busy P \u00bb UFFIE \"Pop The Glock\" VIDEO |website=Web.archive.org |date=2009-10-08 |accessdate=2016-07-09 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091008042722/http://busyp.coolcats.fr/2009/10/uffie-pop-the-lock-video/ |archivedate=October 8, 2009 }}</ref> In late 2009, Williams worked with the rapper [[Game (rapper)|Game]] on his fourth studio album, ''[[The R.E.D. Album]].''\n\n===2010\u201312: ''Despicable Me'' and collaborations===\n[[File:Tyler, the Creator with Pharrell Coachella2011 0350.jpg|thumb|left|250px|Pharrell Williams, [[Odd Future]] and [[Tyler, The Creator]] performing together in April 2011]]\nIn July 2010, Williams composed the soundtrack to the movie ''[[Despicable Me]]'', produced by [[Hans Zimmer]] and recorded with the [[Hollywood Studio Symphony]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Interview: Pharrell Williams of N*E*R*D. talks his \"Despicable Me\" Soundtrack|url=http://www.artistdirect.com/nad/news/article/0,,7321764,00.html|publisher=ARTISTdirect|accessdate=July 5, 2010}}</ref> In October 2010, Williams and his group [[N.E.R.D|N*E*R*D]] supported [[Gorillaz]] on their ''[[Escape to Plastic Beach World Tour]]''. On the tour, [[Damon Albarn]] recorded a song with Williams but this was not featured on Gorillaz's album, ''[[The Fall (Gorillaz album)|The Fall]]''.<ref name=\"Fekadu\"/> The following month, [[N.E.R.D|N*E*R*D]] released their fourth studio album ''[[Nothing (N.E.R.D. album)|Nothing]]'' through Williams's label [[Star Trak]]. In late 2011, Williams worked on three tracks for [[Mike Posner]]'s second album ''Sky High''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mike Posner: From His Mother\u2019s Basement To Here|url=http://allhiphop.com/2011/12/07/mike-posner-from-his-mothers-basement-to-here/|work=[[AllHipHop]]|accessdate=February 21, 2012|first=JP|last=DelaCuesta|date=December 7, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Williams collaborated with singer [[Adam Lambert]], co-writing two tracks for Lambert's album ''[[Trespassing (album)|Trespassing]]'', which was released in May 2012, including the title track and \"[[Trespassing (album)|Kickin' In]]\".{{citation needed|date=May 2018}}\n\nHe has also collaborated with Pittsburgh rapper [[Mac Miller]] on the ''Pink Slime'' EP. The first track, \"Onaroll\" was followed by \"Glow\". It was produced by Williams, with vocals from Mac Miller.{{citation needed|date=May 2018}}\n\nWilliams composed and produced the music for the [[84th Academy Awards]] alongside composer [[Hans Zimmer]].<ref name=\"84th academy awards\">{{cite news| url = https://articles.latimes.com/2012/feb/24/entertainment/la-ca-oscars-music-20120224| title =  The Oscars: Hans Zimmer and Pharrell Williams know the score for the telecast \u2013 they wrote it| newspaper = Los Angeles Times| date = February 24, 2012| accessdate = March 6, 2012| first=August| last=Brown}}</ref> He also collaborated with [[Miley Cyrus]] on her album ''[[Bangerz (album)|Bangerz]]'' and composed the new intro music for ''[[Chelsea Lately]]'' in 2012. He later contributed four tracks to [[Game (rapper)|The Game]]'s ''[[California Republic (mixtape)|California Republic]]'' mixtape called \"[[California Republic (mixtape)|When My Niggas Come Home]]\" and \"[[California Republic (mixtape)|It Must be Tough]]\"; produced two tracks on [[Usher (entertainer)|Usher]]'s 2012 seventh studio album, ''[[Looking 4 Myself]],'' titled \"[[Looking 4 Myself|Twisted]]\" and \"[[Looking 4 Myself|Hot Thing]]\";<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thisisrnb.com/2011/11/usher-hits-the-studio-with-pharrell-jim-jonsin-diplo/|title=Usher Hits The Studio With Pharrell, Jim Jonsin & Diplo|work=This Is RnB|date=November 6, 2011|accessdate=May 6, 2012}}</ref> collaborated with [[Mika (singer)|Mika]] on his new track \"Celebrate\"; co-produced the tracks \"[[Channel Orange|Sweet Life]]\" and \"[[Channel Orange|Golden Girl]]\" from Frank Ocean's debut album ''[[Channel Orange]]''; and is working with [[Solange Knowles]] on her third studio album.{{citation needed|date=May 2018}}\n\n===2013\u201314: ''Despicable Me 2'', \"Blurred Lines\", \"Get Lucky\", ''Girl'' and international fame===\n[[File:Pharrell Williams 2014 Coachella Valley Music and Arts Festival.jpg|250px|thumbnail|right|Pharrell Williams performing at the 2014 [[Coachella Valley Music and Arts Festival]].]]\nWilliams was featured on [[Daft Punk]]'s fourth studio album ''[[Random Access Memories]]'' on the songs \"[[Get Lucky (Daft Punk song)|Get Lucky]]\" and \"[[Lose Yourself to Dance]].\"<ref>{{Citation|title=Random Access Memories by Daft Punk|url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/random-access-memories/617154241|language=en-us|access-date=2019-11-21}}</ref> In addition, Williams contributed to [[Azealia Banks]]'s debut studio album ''[[Broke with Expensive Taste]]'', featuring on the song \"[[Broke with Expensive Taste|ATM Jam]]\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Gore|first=Sydney|title=Azealia Banks Premieres Pharrell Williams-Assisted, 'ATM Jam': Listen|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/the-juice/1568853/azealia-banks-premieres-pharrell-williams-assisted-atm-jam-listen|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=July 5, 2013|date=July 3, 2013}}</ref> Williams penned three new original songs, included alongside composer [[Heitor Pereira]]'s score, for the sequel ''[[Despicable Me 2]]''. These were \"[[Despicable Me: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack|Just a Cloud Away]]\", \"[[Happy (Pharrell Williams song)|Happy]]\", and \"[[Despicable Me: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack|Scream]]\" (featuring [[CeeLo Green]]). His two original songs from the first film were also reprised on the soundtrack \u2013 \"[[Despicable Me: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack|Despicable Me]]\" and \"[[Despicable Me: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack|Fun, Fun, Fun]]\".<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/pharrell-williams-gets-happy-on-despicable-me-2-soundtrack-song-premiere-20130521 |title=Pharrell Williams Gets 'Happy' on 'Despicable Me 2' Soundtrack |magazine=Rolling Stone |date=May 21, 2013 |accessdate=July 27, 2013}}</ref> He also participated in the drummer sessions of the soundtrack of [[Man of Steel (soundtrack)|Man of Steel]] by [[Hans Zimmer]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QTOMIyynBPE |title=Man of Steel Soundtrack \u2013 Percussion \u2013 Hans Zimmer |publisher=YouTube |date=June 24, 2013 |accessdate=July 27, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2013, [[Robin Thicke]]'s single \"[[Blurred Lines]]\" \u2013 written and produced by Williams \u2013 was released. The song peaked at number one on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100, and reaching number one in 13 more countries including the United Kingdom and Germany. It was Williams's third ''Billboard'' Hot 100 number one single.<ref>{{cite magazine | url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1566519/robin-thickes-blurred-lines-hits-no-1-on-hot-100 | title=Robin Thicke's 'Blurred Lines' Hits No. 1 on Hot 100 | magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] | date=June 12, 2013 | accessdate=June 12, 2013 | author=Trust, Gary}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1568185/robin-thicke-still-atop-hot-100-miley-cyrus-bruno-mars-reach-top-10|work=Billboard|title=Robin Thicke Still Atop Hot 100; Miley Cyrus, Bruno Mars Reach Top 10|first=Gary|last=Trust|date=June 26, 2013|accessdate=June 26, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1566519/robin-thickes-blurred-lines-hits-no-1-on-hot-100|title=Robin Thicke's 'Blurred Lines' Hits No. 1 on Hot 100|work=Billboard|date=June 12, 2013|accessdate=July 27, 2013}}</ref> On June 29, 2013, Williams became the 12th artist in the chart's history to simultaneously hold the number one and two positions with \"Blurred Lines\" and \"Get Lucky\", respectively.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1567379/robin-thickes-blurred-lines-remains-atop-hot-100-chart|work=Billboard|title=Robin Thicke's 'Blurred Lines' Remains Atop Hot 100 Chart|first=Gary|last=Trust|date=June 19, 2013|accessdate=June 19, 2013}}</ref>\n\nAs of July 2013 there had been only 137 singles in UK chart history to have sold more than 1&nbsp;million copies; that month, Williams scored two million-sellers with \"Get Lucky\" and \"Blurred Lines\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Blurred Lines gives Pharrell his second million seller in a month|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/blurred-lines-becomes-uks-latest-million-selling-single-2361/|work=OfficialCharts.com|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=August 15, 2013}}</ref> In August 2013, [[Busta Rhymes]] talked about an unreleased \"documentary album\" by Williams where he talks about \"inner-city strife and hardship\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2013/08/busta-rhymes-the-combat-jack-show-chris-lighty|title=Busta Rhymes Discusses \"Scenario,\" A Tribe Called Quest & Chris Lighty \u2013 The Combat Jack Show Episode 3|first=Edwin|last=Ortiz|work=Complex|accessdate=February 13, 2015}}</ref> In November 2013, Williams released the [[first 24-hour music video]] to his ''[[Despicable Me 2]]'' collaboration song, \"[[Happy (Pharrell Williams song)|Happy]]\". Guest appearances included [[Magic Johnson]], [[Steve Carell]], [[Jimmy Kimmel]], [[Jamie Foxx]], [[Odd Future]], [[Miranda Cosgrove]], [[Janelle Mon\u00e1e]], and many others.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://24hoursofhappy.com/|title=Pharrell Williams \u2013 Happy: The World's First 24 Hour Music Video|accessdate=November 21, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140323012659/http://24hoursofhappy.com/|archive-date=March 23, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> It has received approximately 5.5 million views as of Christmas Day, 2013.<ref name=melena>{{cite news | last = Ryzik | first = Melena  | title =Round-the-Clock Giddiness in a 24-Hour Music Video | newspaper = The New York Times | date = December 25, 2013 | url =https://www.nytimes.com/2013/12/26/arts/music/round-the-clock-giddiness-in-a-24-hour-music-video.html?hp= | accessdate =December 26, 2013}}</ref> The music video for the song is nominated for [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Male Video|Best Male Video]] and [[MTV Video Music Award for Video of the Year|Video of the Year]] at The [[2014 MTV Video Music Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|title= Best Male Video 2014 MTV Video Awards |url= http://www.mtv.com/ontv/vma/2014/best-male-video/ |publisher= MTV |date= August 24, 2014 |accessdate= August 24, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title= Video Of The Year 2014 MTV Video Music Awards|url= http://www.mtv.com/ontv/vma/2014/video-of-the-year/ |publisher= MTV |date= August 24, 2014 |accessdate= August 24, 2014}}</ref>\n[[File:Pharrell Williams - speaking on stage - summer sonic2015.ogv|thumb|left|thumbtime=3|250px|(video) Pharrell Williams introducing a N.E.R.D section of his live performance at [[Summer Sonic Festival]] in [[Japan]], 2015]]\n\nIt was announced in December 2013 that Williams had been nominated for seven Grammy Awards, including [[Grammy Award for Producer of the Year, Non-Classical|Producer of the Year]].<ref>{{cite news| url=https://variety.com/2013/music/news/grammy-nominations-jay-z-leads-but-timberlake-other-stars-shut-out-of-top-categories-1200927905/ | work=Variety | title=Grammy Nominations: Jay Z Leads But Timberlake, Other Stars Shut Out of Top Categories \u2013 Variety}}</ref> In the same month, a press release from [[Columbia Records]] announced that Williams had signed a contract with the label and would be releasing an album in 2014, entitled ''[[Girl (Pharrell Williams album)|Girl]]'', featuring the single \"[[Happy (Pharrell Williams song)|Happy]]\" from the ''Despicable Me 2'' [[Despicable Me: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack|soundtrack]].<ref name=\"second album\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2013/dec/18/pharrell-williams-solo-album|title=Pharrell Williams signs to Columbia|last=Michaels|first=Sean|date=December 18, 2013|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=December 22, 2013}}</ref> For \"Happy\", Williams was nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Original Song]]. In February 2014 [[Major Lazer]] announced they would be releasing a five-track EP titled ''[[Apocalypse Soon]]'' on the 25th of that month. The EP, released via [[Mad Decent]] and [[Secretly Canadian]], will feature Williams and [[Sean Paul]], among others. The first single off the EP, which features Williams, is titled \"[[Apocalypse Soon|Aerosol Can]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indieshuffle.com/major-lazer-aerosol-can-ft-pharrell/|title=Major Lazer \u2013 ''Apocalypse Soon'' EP|accessdate=February 6, 2014}}</ref> Williams contributed a verse to [[Future (rapper)|Future]]'s February 2014 single \"[[Move That Dope]]\", which also featured [[Pusha T]] and Casino over production from [[Mike Will Made It]].<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/future-move-that-dope-feat-pharrell-pusha-t-casino-prod-by-mike-will-made-it-new-song.1814367.html |title=Future \u2013 Move That Dope Feat. Pharrell, Pusha T & Casino (Prod. By Mike WiLL Made It) &#124; Stream & Listen [New Song&#93; |publisher=Hotnewhiphop.com |date=February 6, 2014 |accessdate=March 3, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn February 18, Williams announced via Twitter that his second album, ''[[Girl (Pharrell Williams album)|Girl]]'' would be released on March 3, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/pharrell-announces-new-album-g-i-r-l-reveals-cover-and-release-date-news.9416.html |title=Pharrell Announces New Album \"Girl\"; Reveals Cover & Release Date |publisher=Hotnewhiphop.com |date=February 19, 2014 |accessdate=March 3, 2014}}</ref> At the [[86th Academy Awards]] on March 2, 2014, Williams's song \"Happy\" lost to \"[[Let It Go (Disney song)|Let It Go]]\" from ''[[Frozen (2013 film)|Frozen]]''.  Afterwards, when ''GQ'' magazine asked Williams \"how badly\" did he want the Oscar, he responded: \"When they read the results, my face was...frozen. But then I thought about it, and I just decided just to...let it go.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Baron|first=Zach|title=Pharrell Williams on Advanced Style Moves and That Oscar Snub: My Song Will \"Be Here For 10 Years\"|url=https://www.gq.com/entertainment/profiles/201404/pharrell-williams-oscar-snub|accessdate=March 31, 2014|newspaper=GQ|date=March 2014}}</ref> At the Oscar Awards that same year, he wore a controversial outfit consisting of a tuxedo with shorts.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/oscars/pharrell-wears-shorts-oscars-red-carpet-article-1.1708326 |title=Oscars 2014:Pharrell Williams wears tuxedo shorts on the red carpet |newspaper=New York Daily News |date=March 2, 2014 |accessdate=July 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Dear Girl Tour]] was a European concert tour, in support of his second studio album, ''[[Girl (Pharrell Williams album)|Girl]]''. It was Williams's first solo tour since 2006.<ref name=mtv>{{cite news|last=MTV|first=Lisa|title=Dear Girl Tour|url= http://www.mtv.com/news/1829269/pharrell-dear-girl-tour-europe//|publisher=MTV}}</ref> In May 2014, Williams received an Innovator Award at the [[iHeartRadio Music Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1818925/rihanna-wins-big-at-iheartradio-awards-see-the-winners-list/|title=Rihanna Wins Big At iHeartRadio Awards: See The Winners List|publisher=MTV|date=May 1, 2014|accessdate=May 1, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===2014\u2013present: ''The Voice'', ''Something in the Water'' and other ventures===\n[[File:Pharrell Williams - Global Citizen Festival Hamburg 02.jpg|thumb|Williams at the [[Global Citizen Festival]] in [[Hamburg]], July 2017.]]\nOn March 31, 2014, Williams was announced as a new coach for the [[The Voice (U.S. season 7)|seventh season]] of ''[[The Voice (U.S. TV series)|The Voice]]'', replacing [[CeeLo Green]].<ref name=respers>{{cite news|last=Respers|first=Lisa|title=Pharrell Williams joining 'The Voice'|url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/03/31/showbiz/tv/pharrell-williams-the-voice/|publisher=CNN|accessdate=April 3, 2014|date=March 31, 2014}}</ref> On May 18, 2015, Team Pharrell had 16-year-old [[Sawyer Fredericks]] win the [[The Voice (U.S. season 8)|eighth season]] of ''[[The Voice (U.S. TV series)|The Voice]]''. In June 2014, it was announced that Williams would make a guest appearance on the docu-series ''[[Sisterhood of Hip Hop]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Corry|first=Kristin|title='Sisterhood of Hip Hop' to Debut on Oxygen This Summer|url=http://www.vibe.com/article/sisterhood-of-hip-hop-debut-oxygen-summer|work=[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]]|publisher=Vibe.com|date=June 9, 2014|accessdate=June 14, 2014}}</ref> Williams was the executive producer of Atlanta rapper [[T.I.]]'s ninth studio album, ''[[Paperwork (T.I. album)|Paperwork]]'', which was released on October 21, 2014 by [[Grand Hustle Records|Grand Hustle]] and [[Columbia Records]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.power1049.com/index.php/79-muzic-category/news/71-t-i-talks-working-with-executive-producer-pharrell-williams-for-his-paperwork-album|title=T.I. Talks Working With Executive Producer Pharrell Williams For His \"Paperwork\" Album|author=Super User|publisher=Power1049.com|accessdate=February 13, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20141102102804/http://www.power1049.com/index.php/79-muzic-category/news/71-t-i-talks-working-with-executive-producer-pharrell-williams-for-his-paperwork-album|archivedate=November 2, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In May 2014, Williams curated an art show named after his album, \"Girl,\"  at the [[Galerie Perrotin]] in Paris, France. The show included 37 artists including [[Takashi Murakami]], [[JR (artist)|JR]], [[Daniel Arsham]], and [[Marina Abramovic]] among others.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tmagazine.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/05/27/pharrell-curated-exhibition-paris-girl-emmanuel-perrotin-marina-abramovic|title=Art and Fashion Stars Toast a Pharrell-Curated Exhibition in Paris |work=The New York Times|accessdate=February 13, 2015}}</ref> [[Comme des Gar\u00e7ons]] developed a unisex fragrance with Williams<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vogue.co.uk/beauty/2014/03/12/pharrell-williams-comme-des-garcons-fragrance-collaboration-girl|title=Pharrell Williams Comme Des Garcons Fragrance Collaboration GIRL (Vogue.co.uk)|work=Vogue UK|accessdate=February 13, 2015}}</ref> scheduled for release in late 2014. [[Kaws]] designed the bottle artwork.<ref>\"[http://comme-des-garcons-parfum.com/perfumes/g-i-r-l/ Girl by Pharrell Williams]\". [[Comme des Gar\u00e7ons]]. Accessed 23 March 2017</ref>\n\nIn January 2015, Williams and [[Al Gore]] announced that they are teaming up to create a 7-continent \"Live Earth\" concert on June 18 to raise awareness about and pressure governments to act on climate change. He is the musical director.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/afp-pharrell-williams-to-head-up-live-earth-global-climate-concert-2015-1|title=Pharrell Announces 'Live Earth' Global Climate Concert \u2013 Business Insider|date=January 21, 2015|work=Business Insider|accessdate=February 13, 2015}}</ref> On February 8, 2015, Williams made a cameo in an episode of ''[[The Simpsons]]'' entitled \"[[Walking Big & Tall]]\" where he comes to [[Springfield (The Simpsons)|Springfield]] to write a new anthem for the town.<ref>{{cite journal|url= http://insidetv.ew.com/2015/01/22/pharrell-simpsons/ |title= Pharrell to guest on 'The Simpsons' \u2013 exclusive |first= Dan |last= Snierson |date= January 22, 2015 |magazine= [[Entertainment Weekly]] |accessdate= January 22, 2015}}</ref> Williams recorded three songs for the soundtrack to the animated film ''[[The SpongeBob Movie: Sponge Out of Water]]''. He also recorded a song \"Shine\" with [[Gwen Stefani]] for the ''[[Paddington (film)|Paddington]]'' movie. At the 2015 [[Grammy Awards]] Williams performed an orchestral rendition of \"Happy\" with composer [[Hans Zimmer]] and pianist [[Lang Lang]] that included a tribute to the [[Black Lives Matter]] \"Hands Up, Don't Shoot\" movement inspired by [[Eric Garner]]'s death and the events in [[Ferguson, Missouri]]. In 2015, a unanimous jury determined that Williams's 2013 hit song \"Blurred Lines\" was an infringement of the 1977 Marvin Gaye song \"Got to Give It Up\".<ref name=\"usatoday1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/music/2015/03/10/blurred-lines-trial-verdict/24492431/ |title='Blurred Lines' jury finds for Marvin Gaye |publisher=Usatoday.com |date= |accessdate=March 12, 2015}}</ref>  The jury awarded the Gaye family $7.4 million in damages for the copyright infringement based on profits generated.<ref name=\"usatoday1\" />\n\nIn October 2015, the [[Tisch School of the Arts]] at [[New York University]] named Williams as their [[artist-in-residence]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Daley |first=Megan |url=https://www.ew.com/article/2015/10/19/nyu-pharrell-wiliams-artist-residence |title=Pharrell Williams: NYU Tisch School of the Arts artist in residence |website=EW.com |date=2015-09-23 |accessdate=2016-07-09}}</ref> He gave the 2017 commencement address at NYU and received an honorary degree on May 17, 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nyu.edu/content/nyu/en/about/news-publications/news/2017/march/pharrell-williams--the-musician--songwriter--and-producer---to-s|title=Pharrell Williams, the Musician, Songwriter, and Producer, to Speak at NYU\u2019s Commencement|last=Communications|first=NYU Web|access-date=2017-12-10}}</ref>\n\nAlso in October 2015, Williams announced that he will perform with a gospel choir on Sunday, November 1, at Emanuel AME Church in Charleston, South Carolina, where nine black parishioners were shot and killed on June 17, allegedly by a young white man who is awaiting trial. This is part of a program on race relations being produced by A+E Networks and iHeartMedia. Williams plans to speak with community leaders and others affected by the shooting, which dominated the U.S. news media for several days. The two-hour [[Shining a Light: A Concert for Progress on Race in America]] program is scheduled to air November 20, and will also feature a concert to be filmed November 18 in Los Angeles. A goal of the program is to raise money for the victims of racial violence and for organizations around the country working to promote racial equity.{{citation needed|date=May 2018|reason=entire paragraph}}\n\nIn March 2019, Williams and the city of Virginia Beach announced the launch of a three-day music and cultural festival titled ''Something in the Water'', to be held during College Beach Weekend, April 26\u201328, on the Virginia Beach Oceanfront.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.somethinginthewater.com/|title=Something in the Water - Virginia Beach - April 26 - 28 2019|website=Something in the Water - Virginia Beach - April 26\u201328, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.frontgatetickets.com/2019/03/04/pharrell-reveals-something-in-the-water/|title=PHARRELL REVEALS SOMETHING IN THE WATER|date=March 4, 2019|website=Front Gate Tickets}}</ref> The festival, created by Williams as a solution to years of violence on the Oceanfront associated with the aforementioned College Beach Weekend, also featured activities such as an Adidas Creator Park; conferences on technology, racial equality, and the music industry; and a pop-up church service featuring 20 local churches and performances by nationally renowned Gospel artists such as [[Kirk Franklin]] and [[Mary Mary]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wavy.com/news/something-in-the-water-fest-giving-everybody-a-purpose-vb-business-owners-say/|title=Something in the Water fest \u2018giving everybody a purpose,\u2019 VB business owners say|date=2019-04-22|website=WAVY.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-12}}</ref>  The festival featured solo performances by [[Travis Scott]], [[SZA (singer)|SZA]], [[J Balvin]], [[Chris Brown]], [[Anderson .Paak]], [[Jhen\u00e9 Aiko]], [[Kaytranada]], [[Pusha T]], [[Charlie Wilson (singer)|Charlie Wilson]], [[Teddy Riley]], [[D.R.A.M.]], [[Rosal\u00eda (singer)|Rosal\u00eda]], [[A$AP Ferg]], and [[Mac DeMarco]], in addition to the \"Pharrell and Friends\" set that closed the festival's second day, featuring Williams and a lineup of guests, including [[Jay-Z]], [[Snoop Dogg]], [[Sean Combs|Diddy]], [[Missy Elliott]], [[Timbaland]], [[Usher (musician)|Usher]], [[N.E.R.D.]], [[Busta Rhymes]], and [[Tyler, the Creator]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/pharrell-jay-z-snoop-diddy-something-in-the-water-concert-828250/|title=Pharrell Brought Out Every Rapper Ever for His Something in the Water Set|last=Newman|first=Jason|last2=Newman|first2=Jason|date=2019-04-28|website=Rolling Stone|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-12}}</ref>  Additional guest appearances during the festival's final day included [[Trey Songz]], [[Fabolous]], [[Lil Duval]] and members of [[SWV]] and [[BLACKstreet]].<ref>https://respect-mag.com/2019/04/something-in-the-water-festival-recap-pharrell-gives-virginia-something-to-be-proud-of/></ref> Acts such as the [[Dave Matthews Band]], [[Migos]], [[Janelle Mon\u00e1e]], and [[Lil Uzi Vert]] were slated to perform on Friday, August 26, but were cancelled due to severe thunderstorms.\n<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pilotonline.com/entertainment/festivals/article_4d2e1400-6827-11e9-ae09-ab728c31c230.html|title=Something in the Water cancels Friday's shows after severe weather|last=Matray|first=Gordon Rago, Margaret|website=Virginian-Pilot|language=en|access-date=2019-06-12}}</ref>\n\nWilliams is set to produce five songs for [[Walt Disney Pictures]]'s ''[[The Lion King (2019 film)|The Lion King]]'', marking his third collaboration with composer [[Hans Zimmer]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/the-lion-king-soundtrack-details-new-song|title=\u2018The Lion King\u2019 Soundtrack Details Revealed; Includes New Elton John Song|first=Adam|last=Chitwood|website=[[Collider]]|date=June 24, 2019|accessdate=June 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Influences==\nIn the past, Williams has stated that he does not have any direct musical influences,<ref name=\"VH1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.vh1.com/news/articles/1538022/story.jhtml|title=Pharrell Williams, Accidental Crooner|last=Kondo|first=Toshitaka|work=[[VH1]]|accessdate=July 6, 2009}}</ref> but he has expressed his admiration for several musicians, including [[Michael Jackson]], [[J Dilla]], [[Stevie Wonder]], [[Donny Hathaway]], [[Marvin Gaye]], [[Rakim]], [[Q-Tip (musician)|Q-Tip]] and [[David Bowie]].<ref name=\"VH1\"/><ref name=\"Rolling Stone\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/8798649/qa_pharrell_williams|title=Q&A: Pharrell Williams|last=Scaggs|first=Austin|date=November 17, 2005|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|publisher=[[Jann Wenner|Wenner Media]]|accessdate=July 6, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-35279642 | title= David Bowie: Friends and stars pay tribute | work=BBC News | date=January 11, 2016 | accessdate=February 9, 2016}}</ref> Williams explained that [[A Tribe Called Quest]]'s 1990 album, ''[[People's Instinctive Travels and the Paths of Rhythm]]'', caused a \"turning point\" in his life, which \"made him see that music was art\".<ref name=\"Rolling Stone\"/>\n\n==Business ventures==\nIn May 2012, Williams launched [[i am OTHER]], a multimedia creative collective and record label; i am OTHER also serves as an umbrella for his additional business endeavors, including a dedicated YouTube channel and apparel/textile lines.\n\nIn 2005, Williams partnered with Japanese fashion icon [[Nigo]] to create the streetwear brands [[Billionaire Boys Club (clothing retailer)|Billionaire Boys Club]] and [[Billionaire Boys Club (clothing retailer)|Ice Cream]] footwear. BBC has flagship store in [[SoHo]], [[New York City]] and an official Ice Cream store in [[Tokyo]], [[Japan]]. Several stores that retail Billionaire Boys Club and Ice Cream clothing exist across North America, the [[United Kingdom]] and Europe, as well as Asia and the Middle East.  Pharrell and Nigo went on to launch the Billionaire Girls Club.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbcicecream.com/shop/bgc/ |title=Shop Billionaire Girls Club at BBCIcecream |website=Bbcicecream.com |date=2016-06-23 |accessdate=2016-07-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151006235345/http://www.bbcicecream.com/shop/bgc/ |archivedate=October 6, 2015 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, Williams co-designed a series of jewelry (\"Blason\") and glasses for [[Louis Vuitton]].<ref name=\"touchstone\">{{cite news|url=http://www.theaustralian.news.com.au/story/0,25197,25111550-5013575,00.html|title=Hip-hop's glittering touchstone|date=February 27, 2009|work=[[The Australian]]|publisher=[[News Corporation (1980\u20132013)|News Corporation]]|accessdate=March 11, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090304144009/http://www.theaustralian.news.com.au/story/0,25197,25111550-5013575,00.html|archive-date=March 4, 2009|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> He has also worked on furniture with [[Emmanuel Perrotin]] and a French manufacturer, Domeau & P\u00e9r\u00e8s. One of his works, a molded plastic seat with human legs, was created because he \"wanted to know what it was like to be in love.\" The chair depicts a sexual scene with a pair of female legs and male legs.\n\nIn 2009, Williams unveiled a collaborative sculpture with [[Takashi Murakami]] at [[Art Basel]], which spoke to the metaphor of value.<ref name=\"Interview with Pharrell Williams Art 40 Basel 2009\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vsKrADTeEuE|title=Interview with Pharrell Williams at Art Basel 2009|date=June 11, 2009|work=YouTube|accessdate=February 13, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2011, it was announced that Williams would serve as Creative Director of [[KarmaloopTV]] alongside founder and CEO [[Greg Selkoe]] and former [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]] president Katie McEnroe.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/pharrell-williams-named-creative-director-186878 |title=Pharrell Williams Named Creative Director at Karmaloop TV |magazine=The Hollywood Reporter |date= May 9, 2011|accessdate=March 28, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn August 1, 2011, Williams launched his new YouTube channel, \"[[i am OTHER]]\" as part of YouTube's $100 million [[YouTube Original Channel Initiative|original channel initiative]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.16239/title.pharrell-williams-launches-his-new-label-i-am-other-records|title=Pharrell Williams Launches His New Label, i am Other Records|author=HipHopDX|date=August 1, 2011|work=HipHopDX|accessdate=February 13, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2013, Williams created a line of sunglasses for [[Moncler]] called \"Moncler Lunettes\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.highsnobiety.com/2013/08/30/first-look-pharrell-x-moncler-lunettes-sunglasses-collection/|title=First Look: Pharrell x Moncler Lunettes Sunglasses Collection|work=Highsnobiety|accessdate=February 13, 2015}}</ref> In 2014, Williams entered a long-term partnership with [[Adidas]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwd.com/markets-news/intimates-activewear/pharrell-williams-to-collaborate-with-adidas-7618802?module=hp-markets/|title=Pharrell to Collaborate With Adidas|author=David Yi|work=WWD|accessdate=February 13, 2015}}</ref> His Adidas NMD \"Human Race\" collection was released on July 23, 2016.\n<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/pharrells-human-race-adidas-nmd-will-release-this-weekend-news.22927.html? |title=Adidas NMD \"Human Race\" collection to be released on July 23, 2016 |last=Rooney |first=Kyle |date=18 July 2016 |access-date=18 July 2016}}</ref> In February 2014, Williams announced a collaboration between [[G-Star Raw]] and his textile company Bionic Yarn called \"RAW for the Oceans,\" a collection of denim made from recycled plastic that is found in the ocean. The project was presented at the [[American Museum of Natural History]] in New York City.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/life-style/fashion/pharrell-williams-g-star-launch-eco-friendly-denim-line-article-1.1608290|title=Pharrell Williams, G-Star to launch eco-friendly denim line|work=NY Daily News|accessdate=February 13, 2015}}</ref>\nWilliams later appeared on a cover designed by French artist [[Gr\u00e9goire Guillemin]] of New York-based men fashion magazine Adon, covering the collaboration.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.adonmagazine.com/editorials/adon-magazine-issue-10-nyfw-september-2014-issue-featuring-pharrell-williams|title=Adon Magazine, August 2014 issue,|publisher=adonmagazine.com|accessdate=August 1, 2014}}</ref> Williams released a collection for retail giant [[Uniqlo]] in April 2014 entitled \"[[i am OTHER]]\". It was created with [[Nigo]], creative director of UT, the company's T-shirt division.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vogue.co.uk/news/2014/04/02/pharrell-williams-collection-for-uniqlo-t-shirt-collaboration|title=Pharrell Williams Collection For Uniqlo T-shirt Collaboration  (Vogue.co.uk)|work=Vogue UK|accessdate=February 13, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2014, artist collective Rizzoli published a book by [[FriendsWithYou]], ''We Are Friends With You'', that featured contributions from Williams, [[Alejandro Jodorowsky]], and [[Peter Doroshenko]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rizzoliusa.com/book.php?isbn=9780847842377|title=We Are FriendsWithYou Written by FriendsWithYou, Contribution by Pharrell Williams and Alejandro Jodorowsky, Introduction by Peter Doroshenko \u2013 Rizzoli New York \u2013 Rizzoli New York|publisher=Rizzoliusa.com|accessdate=February 13, 2015}}</ref>\n\nWilliams was the [[Executive producer#Motion pictures|executive producer]] of the 2015 [[Crime film|crime]] [[comedy-drama]] film ''[[Dope (2015 film)|Dope]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Dope |url=http://youaredope.com/ |publisher=Official website |accessdate=September 5, 2015}}</ref>\n\nWilliams co-composed ''[[The Amazing Spider-Man 2]]'' with [[Hans Zimmer]], [[Johnny Marr]], [[Michael Einziger]] and [[David A. Stewart]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://billboard.com/articles/columns/the-juice/5770395/pharrell-williams-ebay-beyonce-album-scoring-spider-man|title=Pharrell Talks eBay Collab, Beyonce's Album, Scoring the 'Spider-Man' Sequel and More|work=Billboard|accessdate=February 13, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/marc-webb-hans-zimmer-form-652222|title=Marc Webb, Hans Zimmer Form Supergroup for 'Amazing Spider-Man 2'|first=Rebecca|last=Ford|work=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=February 13, 2015}}</ref>\n\nWilliams owns a non-profit organization called \"From One Hand To AnOTHER\" (FOHTA). FOHTA is an educational foundation. According to its website, its mission is to \"change the world one kid at a time by giving them the tools and resources to meet their unique potential\". FOHTA's vision is to modernize the community center concept by empowering kids to learn through new technologies, arts, media and motivation.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/kellyphillipserb/2014/02/23/pharrell-williams-the-ultimate-charitable-hat-trick/|title=Pharrell Williams & The Ultimate Charitable Hat Trick |magazine=Forbes.com }}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Pharell Williams designed a 1000 euro sneakers in collaboration with [[Chanel]] and Adidas.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://wwd.com/fashion-news/street-style/chanel-pharrell-williams-adidas-sneaker-justin-timberlake-11055165/|title=Chanel and Pharrell Williams Drop World\u2019s Most Exclusive Sneakers|last=Diderich|first=Joelle|date=2017-11-22|work=WWD|access-date=2017-11-23|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nVerizon partnered with Williams on April 26 to launch a tech-fused music curriculum in a nationwide Verizon Foundation Learning schools. The education organization under Verizon Foundation works toward providing free technology, internet access, technology-focused curriculum to under-resourced middle schools.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/8508857/pharrell-williams-partners-verizon-music-education-program|title=Pharrell Williams Partners With Verizon for Music Education Program: Exclusive|website=Billboard|access-date=2019-04-27}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nWilliams married his longtime girlfriend, model/designer Helen Lasichanh, on October 12, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-news/news/pharrell-williams-marries-helen-lasichanh-jay-z-and-justin-timberlake-attend-all-the-details-20131210|title=Pharrell Williams Marries Helen Lasichanh, Usher and Busta Rhymes Perform: All the Details! |work=Us Weekly|date=October 12, 2013 |accessdate=October 12, 2013|first=Stephanie|last=Webber}}</ref> They have a son, Rocket Williams, born in 2008.<ref name=biography.com>{{cite web| url= http://www.biography.com/people/pharrell-williams| title=Pharrell Williams Biography: Music Producer, Musician, Singer (1973\u2013)| publisher=[[Biography.com]] ([[FYI (TV network)|FYI]] / [[A&E Networks]]) | accessdate= January 31, 2017}}</ref> The ''[[Despicable Me]]'' song \"[[Despicable Me: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack|Rocket's Theme]]\" was written in honor of his son.<ref>{{cite web|author=imageplaybuttons |url=http://cluemagazine.wordpress.com/tag/pharrell-williams/ |title=Pharrell Williams &#124; Clue Mag |publisher=Cluemagazine.wordpress.com |date=April 5, 2012 |accessdate=July 27, 2013}}</ref> In September 2016, they announced that they are expecting another child. In January 2017, the couple welcomed triplets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/825751/pharrell-williams-and-helen-lasichanh-welcome-triplets/|title=Pharrell Williams and Helen Lasichanh Welcome Triplets|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, Williams was voted \"Best Dressed Man in the World\" by ''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1507427/20050811/williams_pharrell.jhtml|title=Pharrell Is The World\u2019s Best-Dressed Man (According To Esquire, Anyway)|work=MTV News|accessdate=February 13, 2015}}</ref> He is a fan of the science fiction series ''[[Star Trek]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/arts/main.jhtml?xml=%2Farts%2F2004%2F06%2F07%2Fbmpharr07.xml |title=The nerd who inherited the earth |accessdate=2017-05-19 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070311094953/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/arts/main.jhtml?xml=%2Farts%2F2004%2F06%2F07%2Fbmpharr07.xml |archivedate=March 11, 2007 }}. Retrieved on May 22, 2007.</ref> as indicated by his consistent use of the [[Vulcan salute]] to signify his label name, [[Star Trak]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blender.com/guide/articles.aspx?id=2003|title=Maxim|publisher=Blender.com|accessdate=February 13, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081216121343/http://www.blender.com/guide/articles.aspx?id=2003|archivedate=December 16, 2008|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Williams is a skateboarder and has a [[half-pipe]] inside his home.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.askmen.com/toys/interview_200/210_pharrell_interview.html|title=13 Questions With Pharrell|author=AskMen Editors|work=AskMen|accessdate=February 13, 2015}}</ref>\n\nWilliams is building a $35 million afterschool center in his hometown [[Virginia Beach]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fastcodesign.com/1664105/not-a-joke-pharrell-builds-a-stunning-35m-afterschool-space-for-kids |title=Not A Joke: Pharrell Builds A Stunning, $35M Afterschool Space For Kids &#124; Co.Design: business + innovation + design |publisher=Fastcodesign.com |date=June 20, 2011 |accessdate=July 27, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131212083512/http://www.fastcodesign.com/1664105/not-a-joke-pharrell-builds-a-stunning-35m-afterschool-space-for-kids# |archive-date=December 12, 2013 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> His charity \"From One Hand To AnOTHER'\" is a foundation developed for youth between the ages of 7 and 20 in at-risk communities throughout the country.\n\nIn 2015, Pharrell bought a home in [[Laurel Canyon, Los Angeles]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ballerstatus.com/2015/05/30/inside-pharrells-7-million-los-angeles-home/ |title=Inside Pharrell\u2019s $7 Million Los Angeles Home |publisher=BallerStatus.com |date=May 30, 2015}}</ref>{{better source|date=January 2020}}\n\nWilliams says he now regrets being associated with the song \"[[Blurred Lines]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tonedeaf.thebrag.com/pharrell-williams-blurred-lines-chauvinist-culture/|title=Pharrell Williams claims \u2018Blurred Lines\u2019 taught him about \u2018chauvinist culture\u2019\n|date=15 October 2019|accessdate=18 October 2019|publisher=The Brag|website=Tone Deaf}}</ref>\n\nWilliams offered internships to 114 Harlem High School students. All the 114 Harlem High School students have been accepted to colleges and the purpose of Williams's donation was for the purpose of helping the students become the next leaders to bring about change. Williams stated the mission of the program by saying:\n\n<blockquote>\"History will confirm it \u2013 we are in the midst of another Harlem Renaissance.\" Promise Academy High School commencement speaker guaranteed the #ClassOf2019 with A-list internships at the end of their freshman year of college so they can begin their paths to successful careers.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Maxouris |first=Christina  |date=3 July 2019 |title=Pharrell Williams just offered internships to 114 Harlem high school grads |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/07/03/us/pharrell-williams-harlem-promise-academy-internships-trnd/index.html |publisher=[[CNN]] |access-date=20 July 2019}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Pharrell Williams discography|Pharrell Williams production discography|}}\n\n===Solo albums===\n* ''[[In My Mind (Pharrell Williams album)|In My Mind]]'' (2006)\n* ''[[Girl (Pharrell Williams album)|Girl]]'' (2014)\n\n===Collaboration albums===\n;With N.E.R.D\n* ''[[In Search of... (N.E.R.D album)|In Search Of...]]'' (2002)\n* ''[[Fly or Die]]'' (2004)\n* ''[[Seeing Sounds]]'' (2008)\n* ''[[Nothing (N.E.R.D album)|Nothing]]'' (2010)\n* ''[[No One Ever Really Dies]]'' (2017)\n\n;With The Neptunes\n* ''[[Clones (album)|The Neptunes Present...Clones]]'' (2003)\n\n==Filmography==\n* ''[[Despicable Me]]'' (2010) \u2013 Composer\n* ''[[Despicable Me 2]]'' (2013) \u2013 Composer\n* ''[[The Voice (U.S. TV series)|The Voice]]'' (2014\u201316) \u2013 Himself\n* ''[[Popstar: Never Stop Never Stopping]]'' (2016) \u2013 Himself\n* ''[[Hidden Figures]]'' (2016) \u2013 Producer, composer\n* ''[[Despicable Me 3]]'' (2017) \u2013 Composer\n* ''[[The Grinch (film)|The Grinch]]'' (2018) \u2013 Narrator\n\n==Tours==\n*[[Dear Girl Tour]] (2014)\n\n==Videography==\n{{Expand list|date=February 2016}}\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Title\n!Director\n!Ref\n|-\n|2015\n|''Freedom''\n|[[Paul Hunter (director)|Paul Hunter]]\n|<ref>{{cite web|title=Pharrell Williams Singer releases stimulating 'Freedom' video|url=http://pulse.com.gh/music-videos/pharrell-williams-singer-releases-stimulating-freedom-video-id4003641.html|website=Pulse.com.gh|publisher=Joey Akan|accessdate=22 February 2016}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== Awards ==\n{{main|List of awards and nominations received by Pharrell Williams}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{official website|http://www.pharrellwilliams.com/}}\n* {{IMDb name|1214289}}\n\n{{Pharrell Williams}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = [[List of awards and nominations received by Pharrell Williams|Awards for Pharrell Williams]]\n| list =\n{{Brit International Male}}\n{{Grammy Award for Record of the Year 2010s}}\n{{Grammy Award for Best Rap Song}}\n{{Grammy Award for Best Urban Contemporany Album}}\n{{Grammy Award for Producer of the Year, Non-Classical}}\n}}\n{{N.E.R.D}}\n{{The Neptunes}}\n{{Child Rebel Soldier}}\n{{Billboard Year-End number one singles 2000\u20132019}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Williams, Pharrell}}\n[[Category:Pharrell Williams| 01]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:1973 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:African-American male singers]]\n[[Category:American male singers]]\n[[Category:African-American male rappers]]\n[[Category:African-American record producers]]\n[[Category:American fashion businesspeople]]\n[[Category:American fashion designers]]\n[[Category:American funk singers]]\n[[Category:American hip hop record producers]]\n[[Category:American hip hop singers]]\n[[Category:American male songwriters]]\n[[Category:American songwriters]]\n[[Category:American music industry executives]]\n[[Category:American contemporary R&B singers]]\n[[Category:American textile industry executives]]\n[[Category:APRA Award winners]]\n[[Category:Brit Award winners]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Virginia]]\n[[Category:Columbia Records artists]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners for rap music]]\n[[Category:Interscope Records artists]]\n[[Category:N.E.R.D members]]\n[[Category:Participants in American reality television series]]\n[[Category:Southern hip hop musicians]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Virginia Beach, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Rappers from Virginia]]\n[[Category:Remixers]]\n[[Category:The Neptunes members]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:21st-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:21st-century American rappers]]\n[[Category:Child Rebel Soldier members]]\n[[Category:Northwestern University alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-vandalism|small=yes}}\n{{short description|American musician}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name             = Pharrell Williams\n| image            = \"Hidden Figures\" Screening at NMAAHC (NHQ201612140033) (cropped).jpg\n| caption          = Williams at the red carpet screening of ''[[Hidden Figures]]'', 2016\n| alias            = {{flatlist|\n* Pharrell\n* Skateboard P\n* Sk8board\n* Auto Goon\n* Magnum, the Verb Lord\n* Station Wagon P\n}}\n| birth_name       = Pharrell Lanscilo Williams<ref name=\"GrammyBio\">{{cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/pharrell-williams|title=Artist: Pharrell Williams|work=Recording Acqdemy}}</ref>\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|1973|4|5}}\n| birth_place      = [[Virginia Beach, Virginia]], U.S.\n| occupation = {{flatlist|\n* Singer\n* rapper\n* songwriter\n* record producer\n* record executive\n* entrepreneur\n* fashion designer\n* A&R representative\n* film/television producer\n}}\n| television = ''[[True and the Rainbow Kingdom]]''<br>''[[Brainchild (TV series)|Brainchild]]''\n| years_active       = 1994\u2013present<ref name=\"Sony/ATV\"/>\n| home_town          = \n| organization       = [[I Am Other]]\n| spouse = {{marriage|Helen Lasichanh|2013}}\n| children = 4\n| awards             = [[List of awards and nominations received by Pharrell Williams|Full list]]\n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist <!-- See WP:WikiProject Musicians -->|embed=yes\n| background   = solo_singer\n| instrument   = {{hlist|Vocals|drums|guitar|keyboards}}\n| genre        = {{flatlist|\n* [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n* [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n* [[funk]]\n* [[Pop music|pop]]\n}}\n| label        = {{flatlist|\n* [[I Am Other]]\n* [[Columbia Records|Columbia]]\n* [[Virgin Records|Virgin]]\n* [[Arista Records|Arista]]\n* [[Interscope Records|Interscope]]\n* [[Star Trak Entertainment|Star Trak]]\n}}\n| associated_acts = <!-- Per Template:Infobox_musical_artist#associated_acts this list is for acts that the musician has been a member of, not just a guest artist. Multiple song projects are required to show important collaboration. --> {{flatlist|\n* [[Ariana Grande]]\n* [[Child Rebel Soldier]]\n* [[N.E.R.D.]]\n* [[The Neptunes]]\n* [[Clipse]]\n* [[Daft Punk]]\n* [[Jay-Z]]\n* [[Justin Timberlake]]\n* [[Kelis]]\n* [[Robin Thicke]]\n* [[Ol' Dirty Bastard]]\n* [[Snoop Dogg]]\n* [[T.I.]]\n* [[Teddy Riley]]\n* [[Tyler, the Creator]]\n* [[Usher (musician)|Usher]]\n}}\n| website = {{URL|pharrellwilliams.com}}\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Pharrell Lanscilo Williams'''<ref name=GrammyBio/> ({{IPAc-en|f|\u0259|\u02c8|\u0279|\u025b|l}}; born April 5, 1973) is an American singer, rapper, songwriter, record producer, fashion designer, and entrepreneur. Williams and [[Chad Hugo]] formed the record production duo [[The Neptunes]] in 1994,<ref name=\"Sony/ATV\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sonyatv.com/en/songwriters/637/pharrell-williams|title=Pharrell Williams|publisher=[[Sony/ATV Music Publishing]]|accessdate=2019-12-02}}</ref> producing [[Hip hop music|hip hop]] and [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] music. He is the lead vocalist of the band [[N.E.R.D|N*E*R*D]], which he formed with Hugo and childhood friend [[Shay Haley]]. Williams also owns [[I Am Other]], a multimedia creative collective that serves as an umbrella for all of Pharrell Williams' endeavors, including [[Billionaire Boys Club (clothing retailer)|Billionaire Boys Club]].\n\nWilliams released his first solo single, \"[[Frontin']]\", in 2003 and followed it with his debut solo album, ''[[In My Mind (Pharrell Williams album)|In My Mind]]'', in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/artists/149f91ef-1287-46da-9a8e-87fee02f1471|title=BBC|accessdate=December 11, 2011}}</ref> His second album, ''[[Girl (Pharrell Williams album)|Girl]]'', was released in March 2014<ref name=\"second album\" /><ref name=\"iTunes GIRL US\">{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/g-i-r-l/id823593445 |title=G I R L by Pharrell Williams |publisher=[[iTunes]] |accessdate=February 24, 2014}}</ref> and included the commercially successful single \"[[Happy (Pharrell Williams song)|Happy]]\". As part of the Neptunes, Williams has produced numerous singles for [[The Neptunes production discography|various recording artists]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/news/music/la-et-nerd-01jun01,0,7745056.story|title=LA Times|accessdate=December 11, 2011 | work=Los Angeles Times|first=Chris|last=Lee|date=June 1, 2008}}</ref> Williams featured on [[Daft Punk]]'s \"[[Get Lucky (Daft Punk song)|Get Lucky]]\" which reached the top ten in the music charts of over 32 countries, and has sold more than 9.3 million copies, making it one of the [[List of best-selling singles|best-selling singles of all time]]. The song won [[Grammy Award for Record of the Year|Record of the Year]] and [[Grammy Award for Best Pop Duo/Group Performance|Best Pop Duo/Group Performance]] at the [[56th Annual Grammy Awards|56th Grammy Awards]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/videos/daft-punk-pharrell-williams-nile-rodgers-win-record-year|title=Daft Punk, Pharrell Williams, Nile Rodgers Win Record Of The|date=2014-01-26|website=GRAMMY.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-02}}</ref>\n\nWilliams has received numerous [[List of awards and nominations received by Pharrell Williams|accolades and nominations]]; he has won 13 [[Grammy Award|Grammy Awards]], including three as [[Producer of the Year, Non-Classical]] (one came as a member of The Neptunes). He is also a two-time [[Academy Award]] nominee, receiving a 2014 [[Academy Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]] nomination for \"Happy\" (which was featured in ''[[Despicable Me 2]]'') and a 2017 [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]] nomination as one of the producers of ''[[Hidden Figures]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nPharrell Lanscilo Williams was born on April 5, 1973, in [[Virginia Beach, Virginia]],<ref name=\"Allmusic\">{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p281403|pure_url=yes}}|title=Pharrell Williams \u2013 Overview|last=Kellman|first=Andy|website=[[Allmusic]]|accessdate=March 5, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"The Guardian\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2005/nov/06/popandrock.pharrellwilliams|title=Just Williams|last=Bainbridge|first=Luke|date=November 5, 2005|work=[[The Guardian]]|publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]]|accessdate=December 13, 2008|location=London}}</ref> the oldest of three sons of {{sic|Pharaoh|hide=yes}} Williams, a handyman, and his wife Carolyn, a teacher.<ref>{{cite web|date=October 13, 2003|title=Pharrell Williams|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|publisher=[[Time Inc.|Time]]|url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20148349,00.html|accessdate=November 28, 2008}}</ref> His roots extend for generations in [[Virginia]] and [[North Carolina]], and one of his ancestors journeyed to [[West Africa]] in 1831, prompting other relatives to emigrate from America to [[Liberia]] in 1832.<ref>{{cite web|date=September 2014|title=Why Pharrell Almost Didn't Exist|work=Megan Smolenyak's Blog|url=http://megansmolenyak.com/pharrell/|accessdate=September 8, 2014}}</ref>\n\nWilliams met [[Chad Hugo]] in a seventh-grade summer band camp where Williams played the keyboards and drums and Hugo played [[tenor saxophone]]. They were also both members of a [[marching band]]; Williams played the [[snare drum]] while Hugo was drum major.<ref name=\"Age\">{{cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2004/05/12/1084289744331.html|title=Like the song? These guys wrote it|last=Campbell|first=Melissa|date=May 15, 2004|work=[[The Age]]|publisher=[[Fairfax Media]]|accessdate=May 22, 2007|location=Melbourne}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9D01E7D9143BF93BA35751C0A9629C8B63&sec=&spon=&pagewanted=all|title=Style; The Sound|last=Frere-Jones|first=Sasha|date=February 8, 2004|work=[[The New York Times]]|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|accessdate=March 5, 2009}}</ref> Williams and Hugo attended [[Princess Anne High School]] where he played in the school band; there Pharrell got the name Skateboard P.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2004/feb/08/entertainment/ca-shiver8|title=Virginia is for hip-hop lovers|last=Shiver Jr.|first=Jube|date=February 8, 2004|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|publisher=[[Tribune Company]]|accessdate=March 5, 2009}}</ref> Hugo attended Kempsville High School. In the [[MTV]] show ''[[When I Was 17]]'', Williams stated that he was a nerd and often did things that made him stand out from most of his peers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PPvuIFDYeKM |title=Pharrell Williams \u2013 When I Was 17 (Full) |publisher=[[YouTube]] |date=2013-07-10 |accessdate=2016-07-09}}</ref>  Williams attended [[Northwestern University]] for two years before dropping out.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/pharrell-williams-profile-happiness-is-his-truth-9463049.html?amp |title=Pharrell Williams - profile: Happiness is his truth |newspaper=[[The Independent]] |date=2014-05-30 |accessdate=2018-04-13}}</ref>\n\nIn the early 1990s, Hugo and Williams formed a four-piece \"R&B-type\" group, [[the Neptunes]], with friends [[Shay Haley]] and Mike Etheridge. They later entered a high school talent show where they were discovered by [[Teddy Riley (producer)|Teddy Riley]], whose studio was next to Princess Anne High School.<ref>[http://www.yolk.com/v092/chadhugo1.html]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060508073207/http://www.yolk.com/v092/chadhugo1.html|date=May 8, 2006}}</ref> After graduating from high school, the group signed with Riley.{{citation needed}}\n\n==Career==\n{{BLP sources section|date=May 2018}}\n\n===1992\u201397: Early career===\nThrough working with Riley, Williams went on to write a verse and help produce for [[Wreckx-N-Effect]]'s 1992 hit \"[[Rump Shaker (song)|Rump Shaker]]\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Kimpel|first=Dan|title=How They Made It|publisher=[[Hal Leonard Corporation]]|year=2006|pages=[https://archive.org/details/howtheymadeittru0000kimp/page/124 124]\u2013125|isbn=0-634-07642-6|url=https://archive.org/details/howtheymadeittru0000kimp|url-access=registration|quote=pharrell williams.|accessdate=March 21, 2009}}</ref> That same year, he also performed a small rap solo on [[SWV]]'s second hit, \"Right Here (UK Remix)\". Williams and Hugo met rap duo [[Clipse]] in Virginia Beach in 1993, where they later signed to [[Arista Records]] through Williams' [[Star Trak Entertainment]] imprint in 2002.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/artists/clipse/articles/story/5938804/new_faces_the_clipse|title=New Faces: The Clipse |last=Brackett|first=Nathan|date=September 13, 2002|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|publisher=[[Jann Wenner|Wenner Media]]|accessdate=March 21, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"Yale Daily News\">{{cite web|url=http://www.yaledailynews.com/articles/view/19305 |title=Rap duo 'Clipse' rocks the gangsta hip-hop scene |last=Torbati |first=June |date=December 8, 2006 |work=[[Yale Daily News]] |accessdate=March 21, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070212024815/http://www.yaledailynews.com/articles/view/19305 |archivedate=February 12, 2007 }}</ref> In 1994, Hugo and Williams had established themselves as a production duo under their old name \"The Neptunes\", and assistant-produced \"Tonight's The Night\" from [[Blackstreet]]'s [[Blackstreet (album)|self-titled album]]. Over the next three years they continued to produce occasionally, and some of the results had little resemblance to the Neptunes' sound later. However, some like [[Mase]]'s 1997 song \"Lookin' at Me\" from his album ''[[Harlem World]]'', and the most definite beginning of the distinctive \"Neptunes sound\", came with [[N.O.R.E]]'s \"Superthug\" in 1998, reaching number 36 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], and gaining them widespread attention for the first time.{{citation needed}}\n\n===1998\u20132004: The Neptunes===\n[[File:PHARRELL WILLIAMS by foto di matti.jpg|thumb|left|Pharrell Williams in Berlin, March 2005]]\nIn 2000, they produced the song \"[[I Just Wanna Love U (Give It 2 Me)]]\" (featuring a chorus by Pharrell himself) for [[Jay Z]]'s album ''[[The Dynasty: Roc La Familia]]'', which released as the album's first single.   The song's sound and success sparked the interest of maturing pop artist\n[[Britney Spears]]. {{citation needed|date=May 2018}}\n\nIn 2001, Britney Spears released her third studio album, ''[[Britney (album)|Britney]]'', featuring the lead single \"[[I'm a Slave 4 U]]\", which was produced by The Neptunes.   \nThe song was a defining hit in both of their careers, and it was The Neptunes' first time having helped create an album that debuted number one in the [[Billboard 200]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1449404/20010928/nerd.jhtml|title=Neptunes\u2019 Pharrell Williams Rethinks R&B|work=MTV News|accessdate=February 13, 2015}}</ref> \nThe same year, [[N.E.R.D]], consisting of Williams, Hugo and Haley, released their first album, ''[[In Search Of... (N.E.R.D album)|In Search of...]]'', in Europe, where the first Kelis album was better received.{{citation needed}} The album sounded very much like their previous production work; the group decided that they should make their work as N.E.R.D sound different, and re-recorded the album with the rock band [[Spymob]].{{citation needed|date=May 2018}}\n\nIn 2002 their re-produced album{{which?}} was released worldwide, and the Neptunes reached number one in the U.S. with Nelly's single, \"[[Hot in Herre]]\". In August of the same year, the Neptunes were named \"Producers of the Year\" at both [[The Source (magazine)|the Source Awards]] and the [[Billboard Music Award]]s.{{citation needed}} [[Clipse]] released their commercial debut album ''[[Lord Willin']]'' in August 2002. The album started at number one on the ''Billboard'' [[Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums]] chart and number four on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], fueled by its first two singles, \"[[Grindin']]\" and \"[[When the Last Time]]\", which peaked at number 34 and number 19 respectively on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100.{{citation needed|date=May 2018|reason=entire paragraph}}\n\nThe Neptunes released a self-credited album called ''[[Clones (album)|The Neptunes Present... Clones]]'' in 2003, with songs and remixes from various artists. This topped the U.S. ''Billboard'' 200 Albums Chart. The Neptunes and Williams specifically were also kept in public eye largely due to ties with [[Jay Z]], producing several hit singles for him and two tracks on his ''[[The Black Album (Jay-Z album)|The Black Album]]''. The track \"[[Frontin']]\" was a big hit.{{citation needed}} A survey in August 2003 found the Neptunes produced almost 20 percent of songs played on British radio at the time, a survey in the US had them at 43 percent.<ref name=Age/> The same year, the Neptunes remixed the [[Daft Punk]] song \"[[Harder, Better, Faster, Stronger]]\" for the duo's poorly received remix album ''[[Daft Club]]''.  The track also had a brief rap section performed by Williams.<ref name=\"Fekadu\">{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/music/news/2010-11-04-pharrell-williams_N.htm|title=USA Today: Rapper-producer Pharrell has new CD, big plans|last=Fekadu|first=Mesfin|date=April 11, 2010|accessdate=December 11, 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[N.E.R.D|N*E*R*D]]'s second [[funk rock]]-oriented album, ''[[Fly or Die]]'', released in March 2004. Williams's rock credentials were further bolstered by his appearance at the [[2004 Grammy Awards]], performing [[the Beatles]]'s \"[[Please Please Me#\"I Saw Her Standing There\"|I Saw Her Standing There]]\" on drums with [[Sting (musician)|Sting]], [[Dave Matthews]], and [[Vince Gill]]. Williams received two Grammy Awards that night, one for [[Grammy Award for Producer of the Year, Non-Classical|Producer of the Year, Non-Classical]], and another for [[Best Pop Vocal Album]] for his work on [[Justin Timberlake]]'s hit album ''[[Justified (album)|Justified]]''. They also gained their first UK number one, again with [[Nelly]], and \"[[Flap Your Wings (song)|Flap Your Wings]]\".{{citation needed|date=May 2018|reason=entire paragraph}}\n\nIn September 2004, Williams was featured on the [[Snoop Dogg]] single \"[[Drop It Like It's Hot]].\" The song would eventually peak at number one on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] two months later, marking Williams's first number one single in the United States. The song was named \"Rap Song of the Decade\" by ''Billboard'' in 2009.<ref>[https://www.billboard.com/song/snoop-dogg-featuring-pharrell/drop-it-like-it-s-hot/6900789#/charts-decade-end/rap-songs?year=2009]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121103145651/http://www.billboard.com/song/snoop-dogg-featuring-pharrell/drop-it-like-it-s-hot/6900789#/charts-decade-end/rap-songs?year=2009|date=November 3, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2004, [[Gwen Stefani]] released her first debut studio album ''[[Love. Angel. Music. Baby.]]'' which featured the song [[Hollaback Girl]], which was also produced by The Neptunes.  \"Hollaback Girl\" entered the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] at number 82 on the issue dated April 2, 2005,<ref>{{cite web |last=Whitmire |first=Margo |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/63581/50-cent-nets-a-fourth-top-10-hit |title=50 Cent Nets A Fourth Top 10 Hit |work=Billboard |date=March 24, 2005 |accessdate=February 3, 2016}}</ref> and within six weeks of its release, it had reached the top of the chart,<ref>{{cite web |last=Whitmire |first=Margo |url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/63105/stefani-single-ousts-50-cent-from-no-1 |title=Stefani Single Ousts 50 Cent From No. 1 |work=Billboard |date=April 28, 2005 |accessdate=February 3, 2016}}</ref> becoming Stefani's first US number one.\n\n===2005\u201309: ''In My Mind''===\n[[File:Astronaut Leland Melvin, and Pharrell Williams present montage to Quincy Jones.jpg|right|thumb|230px|Williams and American astronaut [[Leland D. Melvin]] present a montage to record producer [[Quincy Jones]].]]\nOn September 9, 2005, Williams performed the opening single from his first solo album ''[[In My Mind (Pharrell album)|In My Mind]]'', \"[[Can I Have It Like That]]\", featuring [[Gwen Stefani]]. The single did poorly in the US, reaching only number 48. It fared better in the UK, reaching number three. Between then and the July 25, 2006 release of ''In My Mind'', he released \"[[Angel (Pharrell Williams song)|Angel]]\" (in Europe only), and later \"[[Number One (Pharrell Williams song)|Number One]]\" with [[Kanye West]]. Several songs leaked to the internet before the album release, most notably \"[[In My Mind (Pharrell Williams album)|Mamacita]]\" featuring [[Daddy Yankee]], which was subsequently cut from the final version. \"[[In My Mind (Pharrell Williams album)|That Girl]]\" featuring [[Snoop Dogg]] was the final single.{{citation needed|date=May 2018|reason=entire paragraph}}\n\nIn 2006, the Neptunes produced [[Clipse]]'s second album ''[[Hell Hath No Fury (Clipse album)|Hell Hath No Fury]]''. Most critics labeled the album the Neptunes best production in years, and put the duo back in the charts.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Hell-Hath-No-Fury-Clipse/dp/B0000TWMDY |title=Hell Hath No Fury: Clipse: Music: Reviews, Prices & more |publisher=Amazon.com |date= |accessdate=November 5, 2010}}</ref> A year later, Williams collaborated with [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]], on the song \"[[Hey You (Madonna song)|Hey You]]\", which was available for download on the [[MSN]] website. 25 cents for each of the first one million downloads was donated to the [[Alliance for Climate Protection]], in support of [[Live Earth]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://liveearth.msn.com/green/Madonnadownload |title=Retrieved on May 22, 2007 |publisher=Liveearth.msn.com |date=September 15, 2010 |accessdate=November 5, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080821085106/http://liveearth.msn.com/green/madonnadownload/ |archivedate=August 21, 2008 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Later that year, Williams performed songs at the [[Concert for Diana]] on July 1, 2007. On July 7, he performed at the [[Live Earth concert, Rio de Janeiro|Brazilian leg]] of [[Live Earth (2007 concert)|Live Earth]] in Rio de Janeiro.\n\nA remix album of Williams's solo debut, ''In My Mind'', titled ''Out of My Mind'', was recorded with his newly formed band \"The Yessirs\" featuring [[Questlove]] of [[the Roots]], and was produced by Questlove and keyboardist [[James Poyser]]. However, Williams's record label [[Interscope Records]] did not think that the album would sell well and subsequently was shelved.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thehiphopicon.com/pharrell.htm|title=Pharrell Williams goes Out of His Mind|author=TheHipHopIcon.com|date=September 14, 2007|publisher=TheHipHopIcon.com|accessdate=September 16, 2007}}</ref> The album has built up a strong fanbase asking for its release. The tracks started appearing on Questlove's MySpace, and with every 10,000 plays, a new song was made available. As of July 4, 2007, the full CD has leaked onto the internet along with two songs not featured on ''In My Mind'':  a remix of \"Mamacita\" and \"Creamsickle\".{{citation needed|date=May 2018}}\n\nWilliams produced [[Beyonc\u00e9]]'s version of \"[[Diamonds Are a Girl's Best Friend]]\". He then wrote the Neptunes-produced \"Why Should I Be Sad\" on [[Britney Spears]]' fifth studio album, ''[[Blackout (Britney Spears album)|Blackout]]''. He also produced two songs from [[the Hives]]' album, ''[[The Black and White Album]]'', titled \"[[The Black and White Album|Well All Right!]]\" and \"[[The Black and White Album|T.H.E.H.I.V.E.S.]]\".\n\nIn April 2008, [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]] released her eleventh album, ''[[Hard Candy (Madonna album)|Hard Candy]]'', which featured vocals from Williams and production from the Neptunes on several tracks. In June, an article in [[NME]] revealed that Williams was very interested in producing [[the Strokes]]' fourth album.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/pharrell-williams/37303|title=NME News Pharrell Williams: 'I want to produce The Strokes' new album' - NME.COM|date=June 13, 2008|work=NME.COM|accessdate=February 13, 2015}}</ref> Later that year, Williams worked on a remix album for [[Maroon 5]]'s ''[[Call and Response: The Remix Album|Call & Response]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Cohen|first=Jonathan|date=October 31, 2008|title=Pharrell, Oakenfold, Of Montreal Remix Maroon 5|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Nielsen Company|Nielsen Business Media]]|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1043620/pharrell-oakenfold-of-montreal-remix-maroon-5|accessdate=November 2, 2008}}</ref>\n\nWilliams continued working with a variety of artists, including [[Shakira]] on the songs '[[Did It Again (Shakira song)|Did It Again]]', '[[She Wolf (Shakira album)|Why Wait]]', '[[She Wolf (Shakira album)|Good Stuff]]' and '[[She Wolf (Shakira album)|Long Time]]' for her sixth studio album, ''[[She Wolf (Shakira album)|She Wolf]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/music/a181454/shakira-pharrell-taught-me-a-lot.html |title=Music \u2013 News \u2013 Shakira: 'Pharrell taught me a lot' |website=Digital Spy |date=October 10, 2009 |accessdate=November 5, 2010}}</ref> In September 2009, Williams was credited as a co-writer and producer of the song \"[[Fresh Out the Oven]]\" for [[Jennifer Lopez]].<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/17842/102934 |title=Pink, Paramore, Death Cab, Katy Perry, Ne-Yo and More: VMAs Interviews You Didn't See on TV  |magazine=Rolling Stone |accessdate=November 5, 2010}}</ref> It was released as a [[buzz single]] from Lopez's seventh studio album ''[[Love? (album)|Love?]]''. The following month, Williams made a guest appearance on French rapper [[Uffie]]'s first album, which arrived in early 2010.<ref name=\"Busy P Blog 10/03/2009\">{{cite web|url=http://busyp.coolcats.fr/2009/10/uffie-pop-the-lock-video/ |title=Busy P \u00bb UFFIE \"Pop The Glock\" VIDEO |website=Web.archive.org |date=2009-10-08 |accessdate=2016-07-09 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091008042722/http://busyp.coolcats.fr/2009/10/uffie-pop-the-lock-video/ |archivedate=October 8, 2009 }}</ref> In late 2009, Williams worked with the rapper [[Game (rapper)|Game]] on his fourth studio album, ''[[The R.E.D. Album]].''\n\n===2010\u201312: ''Despicable Me'' and collaborations===\n[[File:Tyler, the Creator with Pharrell Coachella2011 0350.jpg|thumb|left|250px|Pharrell Williams, [[Odd Future]] and [[Tyler, The Creator]] performing together in April 2011]]\nIn July 2010, Williams composed the soundtrack to the movie ''[[Despicable Me]]'', produced by [[Hans Zimmer]] and recorded with the [[Hollywood Studio Symphony]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Interview: Pharrell Williams of N*E*R*D. talks his \"Despicable Me\" Soundtrack|url=http://www.artistdirect.com/nad/news/article/0,,7321764,00.html|publisher=ARTISTdirect|accessdate=July 5, 2010}}</ref> In October 2010, Williams and his group [[N.E.R.D|N*E*R*D]] supported [[Gorillaz]] on their ''[[Escape to Plastic Beach World Tour]]''. On the tour, [[Damon Albarn]] recorded a song with Williams but this was not featured on Gorillaz's album, ''[[The Fall (Gorillaz album)|The Fall]]''.<ref name=\"Fekadu\"/> The following month, [[N.E.R.D|N*E*R*D]] released their fourth studio album ''[[Nothing (N.E.R.D. album)|Nothing]]'' through Williams's label [[Star Trak]]. In late 2011, Williams worked on three tracks for [[Mike Posner]]'s second album ''Sky High''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mike Posner: From His Mother\u2019s Basement To Here|url=http://allhiphop.com/2011/12/07/mike-posner-from-his-mothers-basement-to-here/|work=[[AllHipHop]]|accessdate=February 21, 2012|first=JP|last=DelaCuesta|date=December 7, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Williams collaborated with singer [[Adam Lambert]], co-writing two tracks for Lambert's album ''[[Trespassing (album)|Trespassing]]'', which was released in May 2012, including the title track and \"[[Trespassing (album)|Kickin' In]]\".{{citation needed|date=May 2018}}\n\nHe has also collaborated with Pittsburgh rapper [[Mac Miller]] on the ''Pink Slime'' EP. The first track, \"Onaroll\" was followed by \"Glow\". It was produced by Williams, with vocals from Mac Miller.{{citation needed|date=May 2018}}\n\nWilliams composed and produced the music for the [[84th Academy Awards]] alongside composer [[Hans Zimmer]].<ref name=\"84th academy awards\">{{cite news| url = https://articles.latimes.com/2012/feb/24/entertainment/la-ca-oscars-music-20120224| title =  The Oscars: Hans Zimmer and Pharrell Williams know the score for the telecast \u2013 they wrote it| newspaper = Los Angeles Times| date = February 24, 2012| accessdate = March 6, 2012| first=August| last=Brown}}</ref> He also collaborated with [[Miley Cyrus]] on her album ''[[Bangerz (album)|Bangerz]]'' and composed the new intro music for ''[[Chelsea Lately]]'' in 2012. He later contributed four tracks to [[Game (rapper)|The Game]]'s ''[[California Republic (mixtape)|California Republic]]'' mixtape called \"[[California Republic (mixtape)|When My Niggas Come Home]]\" and \"[[California Republic (mixtape)|It Must be Tough]]\"; produced two tracks on [[Usher (entertainer)|Usher]]'s 2012 seventh studio album, ''[[Looking 4 Myself]],'' titled \"[[Looking 4 Myself|Twisted]]\" and \"[[Looking 4 Myself|Hot Thing]]\";<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thisisrnb.com/2011/11/usher-hits-the-studio-with-pharrell-jim-jonsin-diplo/|title=Usher Hits The Studio With Pharrell, Jim Jonsin & Diplo|work=This Is RnB|date=November 6, 2011|accessdate=May 6, 2012}}</ref> collaborated with [[Mika (singer)|Mika]] on his new track \"Celebrate\"; co-produced the tracks \"[[Channel Orange|Sweet Life]]\" and \"[[Channel Orange|Golden Girl]]\" from Frank Ocean's debut album ''[[Channel Orange]]''; and is working with [[Solange Knowles]] on her third studio album.{{citation needed|date=May 2018}}\n\n===2013\u201314: ''Despicable Me 2'', \"Blurred Lines\", \"Get Lucky\", ''Girl'' and international fame===\n[[File:Pharrell Williams 2014 Coachella Valley Music and Arts Festival.jpg|250px|thumbnail|right|Pharrell Williams performing at the 2014 [[Coachella Valley Music and Arts Festival]].]]\nWilliams was featured on [[Daft Punk]]'s fourth studio album ''[[Random Access Memories]]'' on the songs \"[[Get Lucky (Daft Punk song)|Get Lucky]]\" and \"[[Lose Yourself to Dance]].\"<ref>{{Citation|title=Random Access Memories by Daft Punk|url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/random-access-memories/617154241|language=en-us|access-date=2019-11-21}}</ref> In addition, Williams contributed to [[Azealia Banks]]'s debut studio album ''[[Broke with Expensive Taste]]'', featuring on the song \"[[Broke with Expensive Taste|ATM Jam]]\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Gore|first=Sydney|title=Azealia Banks Premieres Pharrell Williams-Assisted, 'ATM Jam': Listen|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/the-juice/1568853/azealia-banks-premieres-pharrell-williams-assisted-atm-jam-listen|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=July 5, 2013|date=July 3, 2013}}</ref> Williams penned three new original songs, included alongside composer [[Heitor Pereira]]'s score, for the sequel ''[[Despicable Me 2]]''. These were \"[[Despicable Me: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack|Just a Cloud Away]]\", \"[[Happy (Pharrell Williams song)|Happy]]\", and \"[[Despicable Me: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack|Scream]]\" (featuring [[CeeLo Green]]). His two original songs from the first film were also reprised on the soundtrack \u2013 \"[[Despicable Me: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack|Despicable Me]]\" and \"[[Despicable Me: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack|Fun, Fun, Fun]]\".<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/pharrell-williams-gets-happy-on-despicable-me-2-soundtrack-song-premiere-20130521 |title=Pharrell Williams Gets 'Happy' on 'Despicable Me 2' Soundtrack |magazine=Rolling Stone |date=May 21, 2013 |accessdate=July 27, 2013}}</ref> He also participated in the drummer sessions of the soundtrack of [[Man of Steel (soundtrack)|Man of Steel]] by [[Hans Zimmer]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QTOMIyynBPE |title=Man of Steel Soundtrack \u2013 Percussion \u2013 Hans Zimmer |publisher=YouTube |date=June 24, 2013 |accessdate=July 27, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2013, [[Robin Thicke]]'s single \"[[Blurred Lines]]\" \u2013 written and produced by Williams \u2013 was released. The song peaked at number one on the ''Billboard'' Hot 100, and reaching number one in 13 more countries including the United Kingdom and Germany. It was Williams's third ''Billboard'' Hot 100 number one single.<ref>{{cite magazine | url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1566519/robin-thickes-blurred-lines-hits-no-1-on-hot-100 | title=Robin Thicke's 'Blurred Lines' Hits No. 1 on Hot 100 | magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] | date=June 12, 2013 | accessdate=June 12, 2013 | author=Trust, Gary}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1568185/robin-thicke-still-atop-hot-100-miley-cyrus-bruno-mars-reach-top-10|work=Billboard|title=Robin Thicke Still Atop Hot 100; Miley Cyrus, Bruno Mars Reach Top 10|first=Gary|last=Trust|date=June 26, 2013|accessdate=June 26, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1566519/robin-thickes-blurred-lines-hits-no-1-on-hot-100|title=Robin Thicke's 'Blurred Lines' Hits No. 1 on Hot 100|work=Billboard|date=June 12, 2013|accessdate=July 27, 2013}}</ref> On June 29, 2013, Williams became the 12th artist in the chart's history to simultaneously hold the number one and two positions with \"Blurred Lines\" and \"Get Lucky\", respectively.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1567379/robin-thickes-blurred-lines-remains-atop-hot-100-chart|work=Billboard|title=Robin Thicke's 'Blurred Lines' Remains Atop Hot 100 Chart|first=Gary|last=Trust|date=June 19, 2013|accessdate=June 19, 2013}}</ref>\n\nAs of July 2013 there had been only 137 singles in UK chart history to have sold more than 1&nbsp;million copies; that month, Williams scored two million-sellers with \"Get Lucky\" and \"Blurred Lines\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Blurred Lines gives Pharrell his second million seller in a month|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/blurred-lines-becomes-uks-latest-million-selling-single-2361/|work=OfficialCharts.com|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=August 15, 2013}}</ref> In August 2013, [[Busta Rhymes]] talked about an unreleased \"documentary album\" by Williams where he talks about \"inner-city strife and hardship\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2013/08/busta-rhymes-the-combat-jack-show-chris-lighty|title=Busta Rhymes Discusses \"Scenario,\" A Tribe Called Quest & Chris Lighty \u2013 The Combat Jack Show Episode 3|first=Edwin|last=Ortiz|work=Complex|accessdate=February 13, 2015}}</ref> In November 2013, Williams released the [[first 24-hour music video]] to his ''[[Despicable Me 2]]'' collaboration song, \"[[Happy (Pharrell Williams song)|Happy]]\". Guest appearances included [[Magic Johnson]], [[Steve Carell]], [[Jimmy Kimmel]], [[Jamie Foxx]], [[Odd Future]], [[Miranda Cosgrove]], [[Janelle Mon\u00e1e]], and many others.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://24hoursofhappy.com/|title=Pharrell Williams \u2013 Happy: The World's First 24 Hour Music Video|accessdate=November 21, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140323012659/http://24hoursofhappy.com/|archive-date=March 23, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> It has received approximately 5.5 million views as of Christmas Day, 2013.<ref name=melena>{{cite news | last = Ryzik | first = Melena  | title =Round-the-Clock Giddiness in a 24-Hour Music Video | newspaper = The New York Times | date = December 25, 2013 | url =https://www.nytimes.com/2013/12/26/arts/music/round-the-clock-giddiness-in-a-24-hour-music-video.html?hp= | accessdate =December 26, 2013}}</ref> The music video for the song is nominated for [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Male Video|Best Male Video]] and [[MTV Video Music Award for Video of the Year|Video of the Year]] at The [[2014 MTV Video Music Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|title= Best Male Video 2014 MTV Video Awards |url= http://www.mtv.com/ontv/vma/2014/best-male-video/ |publisher= MTV |date= August 24, 2014 |accessdate= August 24, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title= Video Of The Year 2014 MTV Video Music Awards|url= http://www.mtv.com/ontv/vma/2014/video-of-the-year/ |publisher= MTV |date= August 24, 2014 |accessdate= August 24, 2014}}</ref>\n[[File:Pharrell Williams - speaking on stage - summer sonic2015.ogv|thumb|left|thumbtime=3|250px|(video) Pharrell Williams introducing a N.E.R.D section of his live performance at [[Summer Sonic Festival]] in [[Japan]], 2015]]\n\nIt was announced in December 2013 that Williams had been nominated for seven Grammy Awards, including [[Grammy Award for Producer of the Year, Non-Classical|Producer of the Year]].<ref>{{cite news| url=https://variety.com/2013/music/news/grammy-nominations-jay-z-leads-but-timberlake-other-stars-shut-out-of-top-categories-1200927905/ | work=Variety | title=Grammy Nominations: Jay Z Leads But Timberlake, Other Stars Shut Out of Top Categories \u2013 Variety}}</ref> In the same month, a press release from [[Columbia Records]] announced that Williams had signed a contract with the label and would be releasing an album in 2014, entitled ''[[Girl (Pharrell Williams album)|Girl]]'', featuring the single \"[[Happy (Pharrell Williams song)|Happy]]\" from the ''Despicable Me 2'' [[Despicable Me: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack|soundtrack]].<ref name=\"second album\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2013/dec/18/pharrell-williams-solo-album|title=Pharrell Williams signs to Columbia|last=Michaels|first=Sean|date=December 18, 2013|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=December 22, 2013}}</ref> For \"Happy\", Williams was nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Original Song]]. In February 2014 [[Major Lazer]] announced they would be releasing a five-track EP titled ''[[Apocalypse Soon]]'' on the 25th of that month. The EP, released via [[Mad Decent]] and [[Secretly Canadian]], will feature Williams and [[Sean Paul]], among others. The first single off the EP, which features Williams, is titled \"[[Apocalypse Soon|Aerosol Can]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indieshuffle.com/major-lazer-aerosol-can-ft-pharrell/|title=Major Lazer \u2013 ''Apocalypse Soon'' EP|accessdate=February 6, 2014}}</ref> Williams contributed a verse to [[Future (rapper)|Future]]'s February 2014 single \"[[Move That Dope]]\", which also featured [[Pusha T]] and Casino over production from [[Mike Will Made It]].<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/future-move-that-dope-feat-pharrell-pusha-t-casino-prod-by-mike-will-made-it-new-song.1814367.html |title=Future \u2013 Move That Dope Feat. Pharrell, Pusha T & Casino (Prod. By Mike WiLL Made It) &#124; Stream & Listen [New Song&#93; |publisher=Hotnewhiphop.com |date=February 6, 2014 |accessdate=March 3, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn February 18, Williams announced via Twitter that his second album, ''[[Girl (Pharrell Williams album)|Girl]]'' would be released on March 3, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/pharrell-announces-new-album-g-i-r-l-reveals-cover-and-release-date-news.9416.html |title=Pharrell Announces New Album \"Girl\"; Reveals Cover & Release Date |publisher=Hotnewhiphop.com |date=February 19, 2014 |accessdate=March 3, 2014}}</ref> At the [[86th Academy Awards]] on March 2, 2014, Williams's song \"Happy\" lost to \"[[Let It Go (Disney song)|Let It Go]]\" from ''[[Frozen (2013 film)|Frozen]]''.  Afterwards, when ''GQ'' magazine asked Williams \"how badly\" did he want the Oscar, he responded: \"When they read the results, my face was...frozen. But then I thought about it, and I just decided just to...let it go.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Baron|first=Zach|title=Pharrell Williams on Advanced Style Moves and That Oscar Snub: My Song Will \"Be Here For 10 Years\"|url=https://www.gq.com/entertainment/profiles/201404/pharrell-williams-oscar-snub|accessdate=March 31, 2014|newspaper=GQ|date=March 2014}}</ref> At the Oscar Awards that same year, he wore a controversial outfit consisting of a tuxedo with shorts.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/oscars/pharrell-wears-shorts-oscars-red-carpet-article-1.1708326 |title=Oscars 2014:Pharrell Williams wears tuxedo shorts on the red carpet |newspaper=New York Daily News |date=March 2, 2014 |accessdate=July 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Dear Girl Tour]] was a European concert tour, in support of his second studio album, ''[[Girl (Pharrell Williams album)|Girl]]''. It was Williams's first solo tour since 2006.<ref name=mtv>{{cite news|last=MTV|first=Lisa|title=Dear Girl Tour|url= http://www.mtv.com/news/1829269/pharrell-dear-girl-tour-europe//|publisher=MTV}}</ref> In May 2014, Williams received an Innovator Award at the [[iHeartRadio Music Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1818925/rihanna-wins-big-at-iheartradio-awards-see-the-winners-list/|title=Rihanna Wins Big At iHeartRadio Awards: See The Winners List|publisher=MTV|date=May 1, 2014|accessdate=May 1, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===2014\u2013present: ''The Voice'', ''Something in the Water'' and other ventures===\n[[File:Pharrell Williams - Global Citizen Festival Hamburg 02.jpg|thumb|Williams at the [[Global Citizen Festival]] in [[Hamburg]], July 2017.]]\nOn March 31, 2014, Williams was announced as a new coach for the [[The Voice (U.S. season 7)|seventh season]] of ''[[The Voice (U.S. TV series)|The Voice]]'', replacing [[CeeLo Green]].<ref name=respers>{{cite news|last=Respers|first=Lisa|title=Pharrell Williams joining 'The Voice'|url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/03/31/showbiz/tv/pharrell-williams-the-voice/|publisher=CNN|accessdate=April 3, 2014|date=March 31, 2014}}</ref> On May 18, 2015, Team Pharrell had 16-year-old [[Sawyer Fredericks]] win the [[The Voice (U.S. season 8)|eighth season]] of ''[[The Voice (U.S. TV series)|The Voice]]''. In June 2014, it was announced that Williams would make a guest appearance on the docu-series ''[[Sisterhood of Hip Hop]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Corry|first=Kristin|title='Sisterhood of Hip Hop' to Debut on Oxygen This Summer|url=http://www.vibe.com/article/sisterhood-of-hip-hop-debut-oxygen-summer|work=[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe]]|publisher=Vibe.com|date=June 9, 2014|accessdate=June 14, 2014}}</ref> Williams was the executive producer of Atlanta rapper [[T.I.]]'s ninth studio album, ''[[Paperwork (T.I. album)|Paperwork]]'', which was released on October 21, 2014 by [[Grand Hustle Records|Grand Hustle]] and [[Columbia Records]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.power1049.com/index.php/79-muzic-category/news/71-t-i-talks-working-with-executive-producer-pharrell-williams-for-his-paperwork-album|title=T.I. Talks Working With Executive Producer Pharrell Williams For His \"Paperwork\" Album|author=Super User|publisher=Power1049.com|accessdate=February 13, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20141102102804/http://www.power1049.com/index.php/79-muzic-category/news/71-t-i-talks-working-with-executive-producer-pharrell-williams-for-his-paperwork-album|archivedate=November 2, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> In May 2014, Williams curated an art show named after his album, \"Girl,\"  at the [[Galerie Perrotin]] in Paris, France. The show included 37 artists including [[Takashi Murakami]], [[JR (artist)|JR]], [[Daniel Arsham]], and [[Marina Abramovic]] among others.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tmagazine.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/05/27/pharrell-curated-exhibition-paris-girl-emmanuel-perrotin-marina-abramovic|title=Art and Fashion Stars Toast a Pharrell-Curated Exhibition in Paris |work=The New York Times|accessdate=February 13, 2015}}</ref> [[Comme des Gar\u00e7ons]] developed a unisex fragrance with Williams<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vogue.co.uk/beauty/2014/03/12/pharrell-williams-comme-des-garcons-fragrance-collaboration-girl|title=Pharrell Williams Comme Des Garcons Fragrance Collaboration GIRL (Vogue.co.uk)|work=Vogue UK|accessdate=February 13, 2015}}</ref> scheduled for release in late 2014. [[Kaws]] designed the bottle artwork.<ref>\"[http://comme-des-garcons-parfum.com/perfumes/g-i-r-l/ Girl by Pharrell Williams]\". [[Comme des Gar\u00e7ons]]. Accessed 23 March 2017</ref>\n\nIn January 2015, Williams and [[Al Gore]] announced that they are teaming up to create a 7-continent \"Live Earth\" concert on June 18 to raise awareness about and pressure governments to act on climate change. He is the musical director.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/afp-pharrell-williams-to-head-up-live-earth-global-climate-concert-2015-1|title=Pharrell Announces 'Live Earth' Global Climate Concert \u2013 Business Insider|date=January 21, 2015|work=Business Insider|accessdate=February 13, 2015}}</ref> On February 8, 2015, Williams made a cameo in an episode of ''[[The Simpsons]]'' entitled \"[[Walking Big & Tall]]\" where he comes to [[Springfield (The Simpsons)|Springfield]] to write a new anthem for the town.<ref>{{cite journal|url= http://insidetv.ew.com/2015/01/22/pharrell-simpsons/ |title= Pharrell to guest on 'The Simpsons' \u2013 exclusive |first= Dan |last= Snierson |date= January 22, 2015 |magazine= [[Entertainment Weekly]] |accessdate= January 22, 2015}}</ref> Williams recorded three songs for the soundtrack to the animated film ''[[The SpongeBob Movie: Sponge Out of Water]]''. He also recorded a song \"Shine\" with [[Gwen Stefani]] for the ''[[Paddington (film)|Paddington]]'' movie. At the 2015 [[Grammy Awards]] Williams performed an orchestral rendition of \"Happy\" with composer [[Hans Zimmer]] and pianist [[Lang Lang]] that included a tribute to the [[Black Lives Matter]] \"Hands Up, Don't Shoot\" movement inspired by [[Eric Garner]]'s death and the events in [[Ferguson, Missouri]]. In 2015, a unanimous jury determined that Williams's 2013 hit song \"Blurred Lines\" was an infringement of the 1977 Marvin Gaye song \"Got to Give It Up\".<ref name=\"usatoday1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/music/2015/03/10/blurred-lines-trial-verdict/24492431/ |title='Blurred Lines' jury finds for Marvin Gaye |publisher=Usatoday.com |date= |accessdate=March 12, 2015}}</ref>  The jury awarded the Gaye family $7.4 million in damages for the copyright infringement based on profits generated.<ref name=\"usatoday1\" />\n\nIn October 2015, the [[Tisch School of the Arts]] at [[New York University]] named Williams as their [[artist-in-residence]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Daley |first=Megan |url=https://www.ew.com/article/2015/10/19/nyu-pharrell-wiliams-artist-residence |title=Pharrell Williams: NYU Tisch School of the Arts artist in residence |website=EW.com |date=2015-09-23 |accessdate=2016-07-09}}</ref> He gave the 2017 commencement address at NYU and received an honorary degree on May 17, 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nyu.edu/content/nyu/en/about/news-publications/news/2017/march/pharrell-williams--the-musician--songwriter--and-producer---to-s|title=Pharrell Williams, the Musician, Songwriter, and Producer, to Speak at NYU\u2019s Commencement|last=Communications|first=NYU Web|access-date=2017-12-10}}</ref>\n\nAlso in October 2015, Williams announced that he will perform with a gospel choir on Sunday, November 1, at Emanuel AME Church in Charleston, South Carolina, where nine black parishioners were shot and killed on June 17, allegedly by a young white man who is awaiting trial. This is part of a program on race relations being produced by A+E Networks and iHeartMedia. Williams plans to speak with community leaders and others affected by the shooting, which dominated the U.S. news media for several days. The two-hour [[Shining a Light: A Concert for Progress on Race in America]] program is scheduled to air November 20, and will also feature a concert to be filmed November 18 in Los Angeles. A goal of the program is to raise money for the victims of racial violence and for organizations around the country working to promote racial equity.{{citation needed|date=May 2018|reason=entire paragraph}}\n\nIn March 2019, Williams and the city of Virginia Beach announced the launch of a three-day music and cultural festival titled ''Something in the Water'', to be held during College Beach Weekend, April 26\u201328, on the Virginia Beach Oceanfront.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.somethinginthewater.com/|title=Something in the Water - Virginia Beach - April 26 - 28 2019|website=Something in the Water - Virginia Beach - April 26\u201328, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.frontgatetickets.com/2019/03/04/pharrell-reveals-something-in-the-water/|title=PHARRELL REVEALS SOMETHING IN THE WATER|date=March 4, 2019|website=Front Gate Tickets}}</ref> The festival, created by Williams as a solution to years of violence on the Oceanfront associated with the aforementioned College Beach Weekend, also featured activities such as an Adidas Creator Park; conferences on technology, racial equality, and the music industry; and a pop-up church service featuring 20 local churches and performances by nationally renowned Gospel artists such as [[Kirk Franklin]] and [[Mary Mary]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wavy.com/news/something-in-the-water-fest-giving-everybody-a-purpose-vb-business-owners-say/|title=Something in the Water fest \u2018giving everybody a purpose,\u2019 VB business owners say|date=2019-04-22|website=WAVY.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-12}}</ref>  The festival featured solo performances by [[Travis Scott]], [[SZA (singer)|SZA]], [[J Balvin]], [[Chris Brown]], [[Anderson .Paak]], [[Jhen\u00e9 Aiko]], [[Kaytranada]], [[Pusha T]], [[Charlie Wilson (singer)|Charlie Wilson]], [[Teddy Riley]], [[D.R.A.M.]], [[Rosal\u00eda (singer)|Rosal\u00eda]], [[A$AP Ferg]], and [[Mac DeMarco]], in addition to the \"Pharrell and Friends\" set that closed the festival's second day, featuring Williams and a lineup of guests, including [[Jay-Z]], [[Snoop Dogg]], [[Sean Combs|Diddy]], [[Missy Elliott]], [[Timbaland]], [[Usher (musician)|Usher]], [[N.E.R.D.]], [[Busta Rhymes]], and [[Tyler, the Creator]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/pharrell-jay-z-snoop-diddy-something-in-the-water-concert-828250/|title=Pharrell Brought Out Every Rapper Ever for His Something in the Water Set|last=Newman|first=Jason|last2=Newman|first2=Jason|date=2019-04-28|website=Rolling Stone|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-12}}</ref>  Additional guest appearances during the festival's final day included [[Trey Songz]], [[Fabolous]], [[Lil Duval]] and members of [[SWV]] and [[BLACKstreet]].<ref>https://respect-mag.com/2019/04/something-in-the-water-festival-recap-pharrell-gives-virginia-something-to-be-proud-of/></ref> Acts such as the [[Dave Matthews Band]], [[Migos]], [[Janelle Mon\u00e1e]], and [[Lil Uzi Vert]] were slated to perform on Friday, August 26, but were cancelled due to severe thunderstorms.\n<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pilotonline.com/entertainment/festivals/article_4d2e1400-6827-11e9-ae09-ab728c31c230.html|title=Something in the Water cancels Friday's shows after severe weather|last=Matray|first=Gordon Rago, Margaret|website=Virginian-Pilot|language=en|access-date=2019-06-12}}</ref>\n\nWilliams is set to produce five songs for [[Walt Disney Pictures]]'s ''[[The Lion King (2019 film)|The Lion King]]'', marking his third collaboration with composer [[Hans Zimmer]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://collider.com/the-lion-king-soundtrack-details-new-song|title=\u2018The Lion King\u2019 Soundtrack Details Revealed; Includes New Elton John Song|first=Adam|last=Chitwood|website=[[Collider]]|date=June 24, 2019|accessdate=June 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Influences==\nIn the past, Williams has stated that he does not have any direct musical influences,<ref name=\"VH1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.vh1.com/news/articles/1538022/story.jhtml|title=Pharrell Williams, Accidental Crooner|last=Kondo|first=Toshitaka|work=[[VH1]]|accessdate=July 6, 2009}}</ref> but he has expressed his admiration for several musicians, including [[Michael Jackson]], [[J Dilla]], [[Stevie Wonder]], [[Donny Hathaway]], [[Marvin Gaye]], [[Rakim]], [[Q-Tip (musician)|Q-Tip]] and [[David Bowie]].<ref name=\"VH1\"/><ref name=\"Rolling Stone\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/8798649/qa_pharrell_williams|title=Q&A: Pharrell Williams|last=Scaggs|first=Austin|date=November 17, 2005|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|publisher=[[Jann Wenner|Wenner Media]]|accessdate=July 6, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-35279642 | title= David Bowie: Friends and stars pay tribute | work=BBC News | date=January 11, 2016 | accessdate=February 9, 2016}}</ref> Williams explained that [[A Tribe Called Quest]]'s 1990 album, ''[[People's Instinctive Travels and the Paths of Rhythm]]'', caused a \"turning point\" in his life, which \"made him see that music was art\".<ref name=\"Rolling Stone\"/>\n\n==Business ventures==\nIn May 2012, Williams launched [[i am OTHER]], a multimedia creative collective and record label; i am OTHER also serves as an umbrella for his additional business endeavors, including a dedicated YouTube channel and apparel/textile lines.\n\nIn 2005, Williams partnered with Japanese fashion icon [[Nigo]] to create the streetwear brands [[Billionaire Boys Club (clothing retailer)|Billionaire Boys Club]] and [[Billionaire Boys Club (clothing retailer)|Ice Cream]] footwear. BBC has flagship store in [[SoHo]], [[New York City]] and an official Ice Cream store in [[Tokyo]], [[Japan]]. Several stores that retail Billionaire Boys Club and Ice Cream clothing exist across North America, the [[United Kingdom]] and Europe, as well as Asia and the Middle East.  Pharrell and Nigo went on to launch the Billionaire Girls Club.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbcicecream.com/shop/bgc/ |title=Shop Billionaire Girls Club at BBCIcecream |website=Bbcicecream.com |date=2016-06-23 |accessdate=2016-07-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151006235345/http://www.bbcicecream.com/shop/bgc/ |archivedate=October 6, 2015 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, Williams co-designed a series of jewelry (\"Blason\") and glasses for [[Louis Vuitton]].<ref name=\"touchstone\">{{cite news|url=http://www.theaustralian.news.com.au/story/0,25197,25111550-5013575,00.html|title=Hip-hop's glittering touchstone|date=February 27, 2009|work=[[The Australian]]|publisher=[[News Corporation (1980\u20132013)|News Corporation]]|accessdate=March 11, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090304144009/http://www.theaustralian.news.com.au/story/0,25197,25111550-5013575,00.html|archive-date=March 4, 2009|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> He has also worked on furniture with [[Emmanuel Perrotin]] and a French manufacturer, Domeau & P\u00e9r\u00e8s. One of his works, a molded plastic seat with human legs, was created because he \"wanted to know what it was like to be in love.\" The chair depicts a sexual scene with a pair of female legs and male legs.\n\nIn 2009, Williams unveiled a collaborative sculpture with [[Takashi Murakami]] at [[Art Basel]], which spoke to the metaphor of value.<ref name=\"Interview with Pharrell Williams Art 40 Basel 2009\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vsKrADTeEuE|title=Interview with Pharrell Williams at Art Basel 2009|date=June 11, 2009|work=YouTube|accessdate=February 13, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2011, it was announced that Williams would serve as Creative Director of [[KarmaloopTV]] alongside founder and CEO [[Greg Selkoe]] and former [[AMC (TV channel)|AMC]] president Katie McEnroe.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/pharrell-williams-named-creative-director-186878 |title=Pharrell Williams Named Creative Director at Karmaloop TV |magazine=The Hollywood Reporter |date= May 9, 2011|accessdate=March 28, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn August 1, 2011, Williams launched his new YouTube channel, \"[[i am OTHER]]\" as part of YouTube's $100 million [[YouTube Original Channel Initiative|original channel initiative]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.16239/title.pharrell-williams-launches-his-new-label-i-am-other-records|title=Pharrell Williams Launches His New Label, i am Other Records|author=HipHopDX|date=August 1, 2011|work=HipHopDX|accessdate=February 13, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2013, Williams created a line of sunglasses for [[Moncler]] called \"Moncler Lunettes\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.highsnobiety.com/2013/08/30/first-look-pharrell-x-moncler-lunettes-sunglasses-collection/|title=First Look: Pharrell x Moncler Lunettes Sunglasses Collection|work=Highsnobiety|accessdate=February 13, 2015}}</ref> In 2014, Williams entered a long-term partnership with [[Adidas]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwd.com/markets-news/intimates-activewear/pharrell-williams-to-collaborate-with-adidas-7618802?module=hp-markets/|title=Pharrell to Collaborate With Adidas|author=David Yi|work=WWD|accessdate=February 13, 2015}}</ref> His Adidas NMD \"Human Race\" collection was released on July 23, 2016.\n<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hotnewhiphop.com/pharrells-human-race-adidas-nmd-will-release-this-weekend-news.22927.html? |title=Adidas NMD \"Human Race\" collection to be released on July 23, 2016 |last=Rooney |first=Kyle |date=18 July 2016 |access-date=18 July 2016}}</ref> In February 2014, Williams announced a collaboration between [[G-Star Raw]] and his textile company Bionic Yarn called \"RAW for the Oceans,\" a collection of denim made from recycled plastic that is found in the ocean. The project was presented at the [[American Museum of Natural History]] in New York City.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/life-style/fashion/pharrell-williams-g-star-launch-eco-friendly-denim-line-article-1.1608290|title=Pharrell Williams, G-Star to launch eco-friendly denim line|work=NY Daily News|accessdate=February 13, 2015}}</ref>\nWilliams later appeared on a cover designed by French artist [[Gr\u00e9goire Guillemin]] of New York-based men fashion magazine Adon, covering the collaboration.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.adonmagazine.com/editorials/adon-magazine-issue-10-nyfw-september-2014-issue-featuring-pharrell-williams|title=Adon Magazine, August 2014 issue,|publisher=adonmagazine.com|accessdate=August 1, 2014}}</ref> Williams released a collection for retail giant [[Uniqlo]] in April 2014 entitled \"[[i am OTHER]]\". It was created with [[Nigo]], creative director of UT, the company's T-shirt division.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vogue.co.uk/news/2014/04/02/pharrell-williams-collection-for-uniqlo-t-shirt-collaboration|title=Pharrell Williams Collection For Uniqlo T-shirt Collaboration  (Vogue.co.uk)|work=Vogue UK|accessdate=February 13, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2014, artist collective Rizzoli published a book by [[FriendsWithYou]], ''We Are Friends With You'', that featured contributions from Williams, [[Alejandro Jodorowsky]], and [[Peter Doroshenko]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rizzoliusa.com/book.php?isbn=9780847842377|title=We Are FriendsWithYou Written by FriendsWithYou, Contribution by Pharrell Williams and Alejandro Jodorowsky, Introduction by Peter Doroshenko \u2013 Rizzoli New York \u2013 Rizzoli New York|publisher=Rizzoliusa.com|accessdate=February 13, 2015}}</ref>\n\nWilliams was the [[Executive producer#Motion pictures|executive producer]] of the 2015 [[Crime film|crime]] [[comedy-drama]] film ''[[Dope (2015 film)|Dope]]''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Dope |url=http://youaredope.com/ |publisher=Official website |accessdate=September 5, 2015}}</ref>\n\nWilliams co-composed ''[[The Amazing Spider-Man 2]]'' with [[Hans Zimmer]], [[Johnny Marr]], [[Michael Einziger]] and [[David A. Stewart]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://billboard.com/articles/columns/the-juice/5770395/pharrell-williams-ebay-beyonce-album-scoring-spider-man|title=Pharrell Talks eBay Collab, Beyonce's Album, Scoring the 'Spider-Man' Sequel and More|work=Billboard|accessdate=February 13, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/marc-webb-hans-zimmer-form-652222|title=Marc Webb, Hans Zimmer Form Supergroup for 'Amazing Spider-Man 2'|first=Rebecca|last=Ford|work=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=February 13, 2015}}</ref>\n\nWilliams owns a non-profit organization called \"From One Hand To AnOTHER\" (FOHTA). FOHTA is an educational foundation. According to its website, its mission is to \"change the world one kid at a time by giving them the tools and resources to meet their unique potential\". FOHTA's vision is to modernize the community center concept by empowering kids to learn through new technologies, arts, media and motivation.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/kellyphillipserb/2014/02/23/pharrell-williams-the-ultimate-charitable-hat-trick/|title=Pharrell Williams & The Ultimate Charitable Hat Trick |magazine=Forbes.com }}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Pharell Williams designed a 1000 euro sneakers in collaboration with [[Chanel]] and Adidas.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://wwd.com/fashion-news/street-style/chanel-pharrell-williams-adidas-sneaker-justin-timberlake-11055165/|title=Chanel and Pharrell Williams Drop World\u2019s Most Exclusive Sneakers|last=Diderich|first=Joelle|date=2017-11-22|work=WWD|access-date=2017-11-23|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nVerizon partnered with Williams on April 26 to launch a tech-fused music curriculum in a nationwide Verizon Foundation Learning schools. The education organization under Verizon Foundation works toward providing free technology, internet access, technology-focused curriculum to under-resourced middle schools.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/8508857/pharrell-williams-partners-verizon-music-education-program|title=Pharrell Williams Partners With Verizon for Music Education Program: Exclusive|website=Billboard|access-date=2019-04-27}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nWilliams married his longtime girlfriend, model/designer Helen Lasichanh, on October 12, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-news/news/pharrell-williams-marries-helen-lasichanh-jay-z-and-justin-timberlake-attend-all-the-details-20131210|title=Pharrell Williams Marries Helen Lasichanh, Usher and Busta Rhymes Perform: All the Details! |work=Us Weekly|date=October 12, 2013 |accessdate=October 12, 2013|first=Stephanie|last=Webber}}</ref> They have a son, Rocket Williams, born in 2008.<ref name=biography.com>{{cite web| url= http://www.biography.com/people/pharrell-williams| title=Pharrell Williams Biography: Music Producer, Musician, Singer (1973\u2013)| publisher=[[Biography.com]] ([[FYI (TV network)|FYI]] / [[A&E Networks]]) | accessdate= January 31, 2017}}</ref> The ''[[Despicable Me]]'' song \"[[Despicable Me: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack|Rocket's Theme]]\" was written in honor of his son.<ref>{{cite web|author=imageplaybuttons |url=http://cluemagazine.wordpress.com/tag/pharrell-williams/ |title=Pharrell Williams &#124; Clue Mag |publisher=Cluemagazine.wordpress.com |date=April 5, 2012 |accessdate=July 27, 2013}}</ref> In September 2016, they announced that they are expecting another child. In January 2017, the couple welcomed triplets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/825751/pharrell-williams-and-helen-lasichanh-welcome-triplets/|title=Pharrell Williams and Helen Lasichanh Welcome Triplets|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, Williams was voted \"Best Dressed Man in the World\" by ''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1507427/20050811/williams_pharrell.jhtml|title=Pharrell Is The World\u2019s Best-Dressed Man (According To Esquire, Anyway)|work=MTV News|accessdate=February 13, 2015}}</ref> He is a fan of the science fiction series ''[[Star Trek]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/arts/main.jhtml?xml=%2Farts%2F2004%2F06%2F07%2Fbmpharr07.xml |title=The nerd who inherited the earth |accessdate=2017-05-19 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070311094953/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/arts/main.jhtml?xml=%2Farts%2F2004%2F06%2F07%2Fbmpharr07.xml |archivedate=March 11, 2007 }}. Retrieved on May 22, 2007.</ref> as indicated by his consistent use of the [[Vulcan salute]] to signify his label name, [[Star Trak]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blender.com/guide/articles.aspx?id=2003|title=Maxim|publisher=Blender.com|accessdate=February 13, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081216121343/http://www.blender.com/guide/articles.aspx?id=2003|archivedate=December 16, 2008|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Williams is a skateboarder and has a [[half-pipe]] inside his home.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.askmen.com/toys/interview_200/210_pharrell_interview.html|title=13 Questions With Pharrell|author=AskMen Editors|work=AskMen|accessdate=February 13, 2015}}</ref>\n\nWilliams is building a $35 million afterschool center in his hometown [[Virginia Beach]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fastcodesign.com/1664105/not-a-joke-pharrell-builds-a-stunning-35m-afterschool-space-for-kids |title=Not A Joke: Pharrell Builds A Stunning, $35M Afterschool Space For Kids &#124; Co.Design: business + innovation + design |publisher=Fastcodesign.com |date=June 20, 2011 |accessdate=July 27, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131212083512/http://www.fastcodesign.com/1664105/not-a-joke-pharrell-builds-a-stunning-35m-afterschool-space-for-kids# |archive-date=December 12, 2013 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> His charity \"From One Hand To AnOTHER'\" is a foundation developed for youth between the ages of 7 and 20 in at-risk communities throughout the country.\n\nIn 2015, Pharrell bought a home in [[Laurel Canyon, Los Angeles]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ballerstatus.com/2015/05/30/inside-pharrells-7-million-los-angeles-home/ |title=Inside Pharrell\u2019s $7 Million Los Angeles Home |publisher=BallerStatus.com |date=May 30, 2015}}</ref>{{better source|date=January 2020}}\n\nWilliams says he now regrets being associated with the song \"[[Blurred Lines]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tonedeaf.thebrag.com/pharrell-williams-blurred-lines-chauvinist-culture/|title=Pharrell Williams claims \u2018Blurred Lines\u2019 taught him about \u2018chauvinist culture\u2019\n|date=15 October 2019|accessdate=18 October 2019|publisher=The Brag|website=Tone Deaf}}</ref>\n\nWilliams offered internships to 114 Harlem High School students. All the 114 Harlem High School students have been accepted to colleges and the purpose of Williams's donation was for the purpose of helping the students become the next leaders to bring about change. Williams stated the mission of the program by saying:\n\n<blockquote>\"History will confirm it \u2013 we are in the midst of another Harlem Renaissance.\" Promise Academy High School commencement speaker guaranteed the #ClassOf2019 with A-list internships at the end of their freshman year of college so they can begin their paths to successful careers.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Maxouris |first=Christina  |date=3 July 2019 |title=Pharrell Williams just offered internships to 114 Harlem high school grads |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/07/03/us/pharrell-williams-harlem-promise-academy-internships-trnd/index.html |publisher=[[CNN]] |access-date=20 July 2019}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Pharrell Williams discography|Pharrell Williams production discography|}}\n\n===Solo albums===\n* ''[[In My Mind (Pharrell Williams album)|In My Mind]]'' (2006)\n* ''[[Girl (Pharrell Williams album)|Girl]]'' (2014)\n\n===Collaboration albums===\n;With N.E.R.D\n* ''[[In Search of... (N.E.R.D album)|In Search Of...]]'' (2002)\n* ''[[Fly or Die]]'' (2004)\n* ''[[Seeing Sounds]]'' (2008)\n* ''[[Nothing (N.E.R.D album)|Nothing]]'' (2010)\n* ''[[No One Ever Really Dies]]'' (2017)\n\n;With The Neptunes\n* ''[[Clones (album)|The Neptunes Present...Clones]]'' (2003)\n\n==Filmography==\n* ''[[Despicable Me]]'' (2010) \u2013 Composer\n* ''[[Despicable Me 2]]'' (2013) \u2013 Composer\n* ''[[The Voice (U.S. TV series)|The Voice]]'' (2014\u201316) \u2013 Himself\n* ''[[Popstar: Never Stop Never Stopping]]'' (2016) \u2013 Himself\n* ''[[Hidden Figures]]'' (2016) \u2013 Producer, composer\n* ''[[Despicable Me 3]]'' (2017) \u2013 Composer\n* ''[[The Grinch (film)|The Grinch]]'' (2018) \u2013 Narrator\n\n==Tours==\n*[[Dear Girl Tour]] (2014)\n\n==Videography==\n{{Expand list|date=February 2016}}\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Title\n!Director\n!Ref\n|-\n|2015\n|''Freedom''\n|[[Paul Hunter (director)|Paul Hunter]]\n|<ref>{{cite web|title=Pharrell Williams Singer releases stimulating 'Freedom' video|url=http://pulse.com.gh/music-videos/pharrell-williams-singer-releases-stimulating-freedom-video-id4003641.html|website=Pulse.com.gh|publisher=Joey Akan|accessdate=22 February 2016}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== Awards ==\n{{main|List of awards and nominations received by Pharrell Williams}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{official website|http://www.pharrellwilliams.com/}}\n* {{IMDb name|1214289}}\n\n{{Pharrell Williams}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = [[List of awards and nominations received by Pharrell Williams|Awards for Pharrell Williams]]\n| list =\n{{Brit International Male}}\n{{Grammy Award for Record of the Year 2010s}}\n{{Grammy Award for Best Rap Song}}\n{{Grammy Award for Best Urban Contemporany Album}}\n{{Grammy Award for Producer of the Year, Non-Classical}}\n}}\n{{N.E.R.D}}\n{{The Neptunes}}\n{{Child Rebel Soldier}}\n{{Billboard Year-End number one singles 2000\u20132019}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Williams, Pharrell}}\n[[Category:Pharrell Williams| 01]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:1973 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:African-American male singers]]\n[[Category:American male singers]]\n[[Category:African-American male rappers]]\n[[Category:African-American record producers]]\n[[Category:American fashion businesspeople]]\n[[Category:American fashion designers]]\n[[Category:American funk singers]]\n[[Category:American hip hop record producers]]\n[[Category:American hip hop singers]]\n[[Category:American male songwriters]]\n[[Category:American songwriters]]\n[[Category:American music industry executives]]\n[[Category:American contemporary R&B singers]]\n[[Category:American textile industry executives]]\n[[Category:APRA Award winners]]\n[[Category:Brit Award winners]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Virginia]]\n[[Category:Columbia Records artists]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners for rap music]]\n[[Category:Interscope Records artists]]\n[[Category:N.E.R.D members]]\n[[Category:Participants in American reality television series]]\n[[Category:Southern hip hop musicians]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Virginia Beach, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Rappers from Virginia]]\n[[Category:Remixers]]\n[[Category:The Neptunes members]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:21st-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:21st-century American rappers]]\n[[Category:Child Rebel Soldier members]]\n[[Category:Northwestern University alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Aitch & Aitch Aitch", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e1998\u20132004: The Neptunes", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pharrell_Williams"}
{"title_page": "Electrical energy in Kosovo", "text_new": "{{Infobox electricity sector\n| country               = Kosovo\n| image                 = \n| coverage              = \n| continuity            = \n| capacity              = \n| capacityyear          = \n| fossilshare           = 97%\n| renewableshare        = 3%\n| greenhouse            = \n| greenhouseyear        = \n| use                   = \n| useyear               = \n| distlosses            = 36%\n| distlossesyear        = 2012\n| translosses           = 2%\n| translossesyear       = 2012\n| residential           = \n| residentialyear       = \n| industrial            = \n| industrialyear        = \n| commercialpublic      = \n| commercialpublicyear  = \n| commercial            = \n| commercialyear        = \n| public                = \n| publicyear            = \n| rural                 = \n| ruralyear             = \n| rtariff               = \n| rtariffyear           = \n| itariff               = \n| itariffyear           = \n| ctariff               = \n| ctariffyear           = \n| investment            = \n| investmentyear        = \n| selffinance           = \n| selffinanceyear       = \n| governmentfinance     = \n| governmentfinanceyear = \n| privatefinance        = \n| privatefinanceyear    = \n| unbundling            = \n| privategen            = \n| privatetrans          = \n| privatedist           = 100%\n| largeusers            = \n| residentialusers      = \n| providers             = \n| transmission          = [[KOSTT]]\n| regulation            = [[Energy Regulatory Office|ERO]]\n| policy                = Ministry of Economic Development\n| renewableenergy       = \n| environment           = [[Ministry of Environment and Spatial Planning of Kosovo|Ministry of Environment and Spatial Planning]]\n| law                   = Yes (2010)<ref>{{cite web|title=Law on Electricity|url=http://mzhe.rks-gov.net/repository/docs/Ligji_per_energjine_elektrike_(anglisht)_dhjetor.pdf|publisher=Ministry of Economic Development of Kosovo|accessdate=30 March 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303215510/http://mzhe.rks-gov.net/repository/docs/Ligji_per_energjine_elektrike_(anglisht)_dhjetor.pdf|archive-date=3 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> \n| renewablelaw          = \n| cdm                   = \n}}\nThe '''electricity sector of [[Republic of Kosovo|Kosovo]]''' relies on coal-fired power plants (97%)<ref>{{cite web|title=Projekti Energjetik i Kosov\u00ebs|url=http://siteresources.worldbank.org/INTENERGY2/Resources/Report_of_the_independent_Expert_Panel_in_ALBANIAN.pdf|publisher=[[World Bank]]|accessdate=2 March 2014}}</ref> and is considered one of the sectors with the greatest potential of development. The inherited issues after the war in Kosovo and the transition period have had an immense effect on the progress of this sector.\n\nRegulation of activities in energy sector in Kosovo is a responsibility of the [[Energy Regulatory Office]] (ERO). An additional factor in the energy sector in Kosovo is Ministry of Economic Development (MZHE), which has the responsibility of dealing with issues that have to do with energy. MZHE prepares legislation and drafts strategies and projects.<ref>{{cite web|title=http://pashtriku.beepworld.de/files/KEK_u_dok./strategjia_e_energjise_kosoves_2009-2018_18shtator2009.pdf|url=http://pashtriku.beepworld.de/files/KEK_u_dok./strategjia_e_energjise_kosoves_2009-2018_18shtator2009.pdf|publisher=[[Government of Kosovo]]|accessdate=2 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Policy and regulation==\nThe main institutions responsible for the energy sector management in Kosovo are: Ministry of Economic Development (MZHE) and [[Energy Regulatory Office]] (ERO). Important responsibilities are also held by the [[Ministry of Environment and Spatial Planning of Kosovo|Ministry of Environment and Spatial Planning]], the Ministry of Trade and Industry, the Ministry of Agriculture, Forestry and Rural Development, and the Ministry of Infrastructure.\nBesides [[Government of Kosovo|government]] institutions, there are also companies with great impact in energy sector such as Kosovo Energy Corporation (KEK), Transmission, System and Market Operator ([[KOSTT]]) and Kosovo Electricity Distribution and Supply (KEDS).\n\nA lot of legislative documents that aim the adjustment of electricity sector have been approved. This includes:laws, administrative instructions and strategic documents. All this legislative framework is drafted relying on [[European Union|EU]] corresponding documents.<ref>{{cite web|title=http://pashtriku.beepworld.de/files/KEK_u_dok./strategjia_e_energjise_kosoves_2009-2018_18shtator2009.pdf|url=http://pashtriku.beepworld.de/files/KEK_u_dok./strategjia_e_energjise_kosoves_2009-2018_18shtator2009.pdf|publisher=[[Government of Kosovo]]|accessdate=2 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Electricity generation==\n\n===Coal plants===\n[[File:Kosovo Obilic Power Plant.JPG|thumb|Kastriot ([[Obili\u0107]]) Power Plant]]\n[[Lignite]] exploitation in Kosovo started in 1922. New mines were opened to satisfy the needs by increasing generation capacities.<ref>{{cite web|title=Coal Mining|url=http://www.kek-energy.com/en/mihja.asp|publisher=Kosovo Energy Corporation|accessdate=1 March 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140227094901/http://www.kek-energy.com/en/mihja.asp|archive-date=27 February 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>  \nKosovo Energetic Corporation (KEK) is a public company, which owns and operates with [[Electricity generation|generation]] assets of electric energy.\n\nThe greatest part of generation capacities of Kosovo are the two power plants: [[Kosovo A Power Station|Kosova A]] and [[Kosovo B Power Station|Kosova B]]. There is a third plant, Kosovo C, currently being planned. <ref>https://energytransition.org/2017/03/14665/</ref>\nThe capacities of the two power plants are lower than the installation parameters level, because of the outdated system and lack of maintenance during the last decade of the 20th century. The first unit of Kosova A power plant started working in 1962 with a power of generation 65 MW. The last unit A5 was built in 1975. A1 and A2 units are out of function and they are planned to be decommissioned. A3, A4 and A5 units are still in function.\nKosova B power plant is composed of two units. The first unit was built in 1983 with a capacity of 340MW, while the second unit was built in 1984 with the same power of generation. The conditions in Kosova B power plant have improved after recent investments.<ref>{{cite web|title=Generation|url=http://www.kek-energy.com/en/gjenerimi.asp|publisher=Kosovo Energy Corporation|accessdate=1 March 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130707034720/http://www.kek-energy.com/en/gjenerimi.asp|archive-date=7 July 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\nThe power plants and coal mines are located in Kastriot ([[Obili\u0107]]),only 3&nbsp;km away from the borders of the municipality of [[Pristina|Prishtina]].\nTechnical and commercial losses and the conditions of the power plants together with the high debts have brought KEK in a difficult financial situation.<ref>{{cite web|title=Termocentrali \"Kosova C\" dhe raporti i Vler\u00ebsimit Strategjik Mjedisor dhe Social |url=http://www.kosovapress.com/sq/arkiva/termocentrali-kosova-c-dhe-raporti-i-vleresimit-strategjik-mjedisor-dhe-social-vsms-53712/?old=1|publisher=[[Kosova Press|KosovaPress]]|accessdate=2 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Hydro power===\nThe only major power station outside of KEK is [[Gazivoda Lake|Ujmani (Gazivoda)]] [[Hydroelectricity|hydroelectric power plant]] which is administrated by the Hydro-economic Enterprise \"[[Ibar (river)|Iber]]-[[Lepenac|Lepenc]]\". Hydroelectric power generation is mainly provided by Ujmani power station with a capacity of 70MW. In the past, Kosovo has had four functional hydroelectric power plants. After the 1999 war they stopped working, but they have been rehabilitated in the recent years.\n*'''Lumbardhi''' hydroelectric power plant was rehabilitated in 2005. A private company has rent it for a period of 20 years. Its capacity of generation is 23 MW.\n*'''Dikanci''' hydroelectric power plant is rented and started functioning in 2010, with a capacity increased from 15 MW to 28 MW\n*'''Radavci''' hydroelectric power plant was rehabilitated in 2010 from a company which has rented it. Its capacity was increased from 15 MW to 30 MW.\n*'''Burimi''' hydroelectric power plant was rented and its capacity was increased from 10 MW to 25 MW.<ref>{{cite web|title=Plani i Kosoves per burimet e ripertritshme te energjise|url=http://www.mei-ks.net/repository/docs/Aneksi_14_-_Plani_i_Kosoves_per_Burimet_e_Energjise_se_Ri-pertrishme.pdf|publisher=Ministry of Economic Development|accessdate=2 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n===[[List of wind farms in Kosovo|Wind]]===\nThere are a few areas in Kosovo where the wind reaches the necessary speed to be used for [[wind farm]]s. \nThe only wind farm in Kosovo was installed in [[Golesh]] by a private company, and started working in 2010. Shortly after, the farm stopped functioning, because the Energy Regulatory Office refused to pay the tariffs required by the company. The ERO officials stated that the plants were outdated. Further studies are required before investments in this field.<ref>{{cite web|title=Renewable energy as an Opportunity for Economic Development in Kosovo|url=http://www.nek.ch/windenergie-geothermie-e/publikationen/dokumente/2013.05.30_GIZ_Study_english_final_16012013.pdf|publisher=GIZ|accessdate=2 March 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304040846/http://www.nek.ch/windenergie-geothermie-e/publikationen/dokumente/2013.05.30_GIZ_Study_english_final_16012013.pdf|archive-date=4 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> In 2018 the firm \"Enlight Renewable Energy Solutions\" bought the rights of a project consisting of 27 wind turbines, and the plants has a planned capacity of 105 megawatts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.globes.co.il/en/article-enlight-buys-rights-to-kosovo-wind-farm-project-1001227695|title=Enlight buys rights to Kosovo wind farm project - Globes|website=Globes|language=he|access-date=2018-06-12}}</ref>\n\n===Solar===\nKosovo has potentials of using [[Solar energy|solar]] energy directly and by converting it to electrical energy, but it costs too much for Kosovo's economy. Solar energy is already used in some buildings and it has benefited to international organizations' founds.<ref>{{cite web|title=Energjia diellore me potencial te madh|url=http://www.telegrafi.com/ekonomi/energjia-diellore-me-potenciale-te-madh-46-15026.html|publisher=[[Telegrafi]]|accessdate=2 March 2014}}</ref> However the sub-company of JAHA-Group \"JAHA SOLAR\" was founded in 2016, and is the only producer of Solar Panels in the western-balkans.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://empowerkosovo.org/blog/2017/08/03/jaha-solar-the-only-producer-of-solar-panels-in-the-western-balkans/|title=USAID / EMPOWER Private Sector  \u00bb JAHA Solar \u2013 the Only Producer of Solar Panels in the Western Balkans|website=empowerkosovo.org|language=en-US|access-date=2018-06-12}}</ref>\n\n==Electricity consumption==\n[[Electric energy consumption|Consumption of electrical energy]] in Kosovo has increased continuously. This is mostly caused by commercial losses. Furthermore, the constant increase of [[Economy of Kosovo|economic]] development and [[Demographics of Kosovo|population]] have increased the energy demands.\nGeneration of energy from power plants has increased year by year, while the generation of energy from hydroelectric power plants has decreased. To cover the request Kosovo imports energy in certain periods of time (mostly during the winter).<ref>{{cite web|title=Strategjia e Kosoves per Energji|url=http://kryeministri-ks.net/repository/docs/Strategjia_e_Energjise_e_Republikes_se_Kosoves_2009-2018_SHQ.pdf|publisher=Kosovo Prime Minister Office|accessdate=2 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Import-Export===\nImport covers 5-10% of the consumption.\nUsually, in Kosovo the imported energy is much more expensive than export. This is because Kosovo imports energy one day before needed, in the other hand energy is exported during the night when the demands are under generating level. Imports and exports have a negative impact for electrical energy price.<ref>{{cite web|title=Strategjia e Kosoves per Energji|url=http://kryeministri-ks.net/repository/docs/Strategjia_e_Energjise_e_Republikes_se_Kosoves_2009-2018_SHQ.pdf|publisher=Kosovo Prime Minister Office|accessdate=2 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Transmission==\nTransmission System and Market Operator ([[KOSTT]]) was founded in 2006. It is a public company, responsible for operation, planning, maintenance and development of [[Electric power transmission|transmission]] network and interconnection with neighboring energetic systems, in order to retain supply insurance in Kosovo. KOSTT is also responsible for the operation of electrical [[energy market]] in Kosovo.<ref>{{cite web|title=About KOSTT|url=http://www.kostt.com/website/index.php?lang=en#|publisher=KOSTT|accessdate=2 March 2014}}</ref>\nKosovo is part of the Regional Energy Community and is connected with the regional system through [[Wide area synchronous grid|interconnections]] with [[Serbia]], [[Republic of Macedonia|Macedonia]], [[Montenegro]] and [[Albania]]. Kosovo is a key point in Southeast Europe because of its geographic position in the center of the region. Electrical energy transmission system is connected with neighboring systems in 400 kV level, except with Albania with whom, this connection is going to start to build in the near future.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kosovo Energy Strategy 2009-2018|url=http://pashtriku.beepworld.de/files/KEK_u_dok./strategjia_e_energjise_kosoves_2009-2018_18shtator2009.pdf|publisher=[[Government of Kosovo]]|accessdate=2 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Distribution==\nKosovo Energy Distribution and Supply Company (KEDS) is a company operating throughout Kosovo having the exclusivity for electricity supply and [[Electric power distribution|distribution]] in the territory of Kosovo. Since May 2013, Kosovo Energy Distribution and Supply split from Kosovo Energy Cooperation and started its operational activities as a joint stock company. KEDS is owned now by Turkish companies \u00c7al\u0131k Holding and Limak. KEDS is considered as one of the largest employers in Kosovo, having 2618 employees. Furthermore, over 450 thousand customers are provided with electricity supply covering household customers, commercial and industrial customers. Currently there are three main projects concerning distribution: Construction of medium voltage distribution facilities of the new 110/10(20) kV Prishtina 7 substation, Expansion and reinforcement of the low voltage distribution network 2013, and Expansion and reinforcement of the medium voltage distribution network 2013. Additionally, KEDS intends to invest 110 million euros on the 5 forthcoming years and 300 million euros on 15-year period.<ref>{{cite web|title=About|url=http://www.keds-energy.com/about.asp|publisher=Kosovo Energy Distribution and Supply|accessdate=2 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Tariffs==\n[[Energy Regulatory Office]] (ERO) is an independent company which sets the regulatory framework founded on the principals of free trade.\nThe energy price is determined by different factors: operative cost, maintenance cost, import and other factors. The decrease of commercial and technical losses would affect positively. Factors that have kept the low prizes until now are: foreign investments as grants, [[Government of Kosovo|government]] subventions, the lack of investments for environment protection and inexpensive labor force.<ref>{{cite web|title=About|url=http://www.ero-ks.org/|publisher=[[Energy Regulatory Office]]|accessdate=2 March 2014}}</ref> \nKEK generating about 97% of the energy has the monopoly of market. ERO has the jurisdiction of setting [[Electricity pricing|tariffs]] for energy services.\n\n==Power plants impact on environment and health==\nEnvironment protection is a mission of the [[Ministry of Environment and Spatial Planning of Kosovo|Ministry of Environment and Spatial Planning]] (MMPH). Since most of electric power is produced by power plants in Kosovo they are considered as the main environment pollutant. Actual emission of gases, dust and waste-water discharged from the existing power plants, are above the levels allowed by the EU directives. According to the [[World Bank]]\u2019s statistics, 835 deaths, 310 new cases of chronic bronchitis, 22,900 new cases of respiratory diseases among children, 11,160 emergency visits to country\u2019s hospital and there is a 100 million euros loss are caused each year because of coal plants.\n<ref>{{cite web|title=Kosovo Campaign Targets Proposed New Power Plant|url=http://www.balkaninsight.com/en/article/kosovo-campaign-targets-proposed-new-power-plant|publisher=[[Balkan Insight]]|accessdate=2 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Energy efficiency===\nKosovo Agency for Energy Efficiency - KAEE is executive institution under the Ministry of Economic Development. KAEE implements energy [[Efficient energy use|efficiency]] policies through evaluating energy saving opportunities and implementing energy efficiency measures in all sectors of energy consumption. This agency has drafted Energy Efficiency legislative frameworks aiming to implement the best EU practices.<ref>{{cite web|title=About AKEE|url=http://www.akee-rks.net/sq/about|publisher=Kosovo Agency for Energy Efficiency|accessdate=2 March 2014}}</ref> The [[World Bank]] is preparing a project of $32.5 million in order to finance investment, and to technically support the strengthening of [[renewable energy]] regulation and policies.<ref>{{cite web|title=Energy Efficiency in Kosovo|url=http://www.worldbank.org/en/country/kosovo/brief/energy-in-kosovo|publisher=[[World Bank]]|accessdate=2 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Cooperation==\nBased on the increase of demand, the role of import is essential to provide stable supplement.\nKosovo has signed several agreements for cooperation on energy sector with [[Albania]]. The fact that the electrical energy system of Albania relies on hydro energy (almost 100%), while Kosovo relies on power plants, is a great opportunity for cooperation between the two countries. Moreover, a 400 kV interconnection line is in its final proceeding before the beginning of building.\nThe kosovar Ministry of Economic Development has negotiated with [[Montenegro|Montenegrin]] and [[Republic of Macedonia|Macedonian]] economy institutions to deepen the cooperation, especially in the energy sector.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kosovo Energy Strategy|url=http://kryeministri-ks.net/repository/docs/Strategjia_e_Energjise_e_Republikes_se_Kosoves_2009-2018_SHQ.pdf|publisher=Kosovo Prime Minister Office|accessdate=2 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n==New alternatives for energy==\n[[Kosova e Re]] is a project for building a new power plant. The building of this power plant would fulfill the needs for electric power in Kosovo. This project has been modified several times. Minister of Economic Development, Fadil Ismajli, claimed that Kosova e Re is due to being built in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|title=Termocentrali Kosova e Re, ne janar 2015|url=http://www.evropaelire.org/content/article/24998805.html|publisher=EvropaeLire|accessdate=2 March 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[Zhur]] Hydroelectric Power Plant project is a new opportunity for using reliable energy potentials. It is evaluated that Zhur HPP generation capacity would be 305 MW. The project is pending because of the high cost, limited capacities and issues that relating with the use of water with Albania.<ref>{{cite web|last=Shehu|first=Bekim|title=Hidrocentrali i Zhurit- Shqip\u00ebria nuk do, Kosova po|url=http://www.dw.de/hidrocentrali-i-zhurit-shqip%C3%ABria-nuk-do-kosova-po/a-5999250-1|publisher=[[Deutsche Welle]]|accessdate=2 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nStudies have shown that beside hydroelectric power plants there are other alternatives to lignite power plants.\nIt is considered that an ideally located solar collector in Kosovo can produce 1600 kWh/m2/year. A study made by Energy and Recourses Group [[University of California, Berkeley|University of California]] claims that the approximate energy that Kosovo could generate from biomass resources is 6600 GWh/yr. While neighboring countries ([[Republic of Macedonia|Macedonia]] and [[Serbia]]) generate a portion of their electric power by using geothermal sites, in Kosovo there is a lack of studies on this field.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sustainable Energy Options for Kosovo|url=http://rael.berkeley.edu/sites/default/files/Kosovo%20Energy%20Scenarios-19-Jan-2012_0.pdf|publisher=[[University of California, Berkeley]]|accessdate=2 March 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130703125656/http://rael.berkeley.edu/sites/default/files/Kosovo%20Energy%20Scenarios-19-Jan-2012_0.pdf|archive-date=3 July 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Economy of Kosovo]]\n*[[Natural resources of Kosovo]]\n*[[Environmental issues in Pristina]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Europe topic|Electricity sector in}}\n\n[[Category:Electric power in Kosovo]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox electricity sector\n| country               = Kosovo\n| image                 = \n| coverage              = \n| continuity            = \n| capacity              = \n| capacityyear          = \n| fossilshare           = 97%\n| renewableshare        = 3%\n| greenhouse            = \n| greenhouseyear        = \n| use                   = \n| useyear               = \n| distlosses            = 36%\n| distlossesyear        = 2012\n| translosses           = 2%\n| translossesyear       = 2012\n| residential           = \n| residentialyear       = \n| industrial            = \n| industrialyear        = \n| commercialpublic      = \n| commercialpublicyear  = \n| commercial            = \n| commercialyear        = \n| public                = \n| public